<DOCNO> AP900208-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in power seven months sudans national 
salvation revolution has done little to revive a collapsing economy 
or end a debilitating civil war that has killed hundreds of 
thousands and threatens more with starvation 
the war is getting worse despite optimistic official talk of an 
approaching military victory 11 southern towns have fallen to 
rebels in recent weeks and the souths largest city juba is 
teetering under siege 
the sudan peoples liberation army led by a renegade colonel 
john garang launched its rebellion against the moslemdominated 
government in 1983 demanding economic and political autonomy for 
the predominantly christian and animist in the countrys southern 
half 
seven years of war have aggravated conditions in sudan africas 
largest country what was once considered a potential breadbasket 
is an economic basket case after 34 years of independence 
sudan still cant make payments on foreign debts of more than 
13 billion it has been ineligible for loans from the 
international monetary fund since 1986 and is in arrears to the 
world bank and most of its western and arab creditors 
meanwhile sudanese wonder whether their nation will become an 
islamic state reviving laws that sever thieves hands and lash 
people who drink alcohol 
sudanese intellectuals and foreign diplomats say the young 
officers of the 15member ruling junta most are in their 30s 
apparently yield major decisions to a 40member council or majlis 
in traditional islam dominated by the fundamentalist national 
islamic front 
they say lt gen omar hassan elbashir the leader of the 
junta vacillates between radical front members and more moderate 
forces 
the brigadiers justified overthrowing prime minister sadek 
elmahdis civilian regime june 30 by pointing out that multiparty 
democracy had failed to end the long war or save the shattered 
economy 
their most visible accomplishment has been a spruceup job on 
khartoum the capital 
rundown roundabouts and squares have been prettied up with 
flowers and gleaming tiles streets are cleaned regularly although 
potholes remain shop facades are painted white with bright green 
shutters 
on the outside things look changed said a sudanese woman 
who like many in elbashirs sudan refused to speak for 
attribution the streets are clean the squares have flowers the 
shops are newly painted 
but the shelves are bare so even if you have money you cant 
buy anything 
the shoppainting gives an insight into the state of the country 
today the choice of green usually considered the color of islam 
fueled rumors that most junta members sympathize with the national 
islamic front 
disbanding the front and other political parties and trade 
unions was among the juntas first acts 
on wednesday elbashir said he would soon announce the 
formation of a oneparty system that would be open to all sudanese 
the front and other political parties remain banned but 
diplomats say its clear that supporters of the islamic front are 
in control 
one diplomat said his embassy learned that elbashir had planned 
on jan 1 independent sudans 34th anniversary to declare an 
islamic state he planned to restore harshly interpreted islamic 
laws or sharia originally imposed in 1983 by former military 
strongman gafaar nimeiri but now largely ignored the diplomat said 
the diplomat said elbashir was dissuaded from the move by 
president hosni mubarak of egypt sudans powerful northern 
neighbor on a quick new years eve visit to khartoum 
the governments public position is that even if sharia were 
enforced nonislamic regions could exempt themselves unlike the 
practice under nimeiri his insistence on nationwide sharia 
exacerbated the rebellion that had begun several months earlier 
and its existence as the basic law continues to fuel the battle 
between the mainly nonmoslem black southerners and the arab 
moslemdominated administration 
the southern civil war still costs the economy 1 million a day 
while causing famine that has killed hundreds of thousands and 
threatens as many more 
elbashir recently spoke of approaching victory over the enemy 
of 30000 trained bush fighters and 20000 irregulars who have 
fared no worse than a standoff for seven years 
the war recently intensified after a lull last year which 
allowed relief to be ferried to desperate civilians but also 
permitted rearming by both sides peace talks are suspended 
indefinitely 
such developments largely because of both sides intransigence 
have triggered protests from the united states egypt and other 
european and arab allies of sudan 
allegations by the londonbased amnesty international and others 
of human rights abuses also have elicited complaints from 
aidgiving countries of the west 
the government denies the charges but diplomats in khartoum say 
one of the major decisions the elbashir government left to the 
islamic majlis was the handling of political prisoners it approved 
torture diplomats allege 
the junta has cowed the opposition after sentencing a doctor to 
death for leading a strike by physicians a sentence elbashir 
reportedly commuted later threats of labor action are no longer 
heard especially intimidated have been the trade unions and 
professional organizations whose strikes and civil unrest brought 
down three previous sudanese governments 
</TEXT>
