<TEXT>
nat wartels chairman of crown publishers and 
considered the richest person in us book publishing died 
wednesday of pneumonia in a hospital he was 88 
wartels built crown into a successful company by buying 
publishers surplus books for as little as five or 10 cents a book 
then reselling them to bookstores for their bargain bins 
the new york native graduated from columbia university then 
earned a degree from the wharton school of economics at the 
university of pennsylvania 
he entered the book remainder business in 1933 and began 
publishing books under the crown name he sold it to random house 
for an undisclosed amount of money in 1988 even before the sale to 
random house wartels was widely considered the wealthiest person 
in us book publishing 
wartels would not disclose his personal wealth but in 1981 
acknowledged that crowns revenues made it one of the three or four 
largest publishers in the united states 
crown was just a part of his business empire other companies 
included outlet book co still the nations leading remainder 
house publishers central bureau the directmail company and 
living language record courses 
wartels is survived by two nephews and two nieces 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

