<TEXT>
the bush administration wants congress to set 
some time limits on how long a borrower can remain a customer of 
the farmers home administration 
under the administrations 1990 farm bill proposals sent to 
capitol hill this week direct fmha farm operating loans would be 
limited to seven years if the borrower also had a bank loan 
guaranteed by the agency that could add another 10 years of 
eligibility making an effective limit of 17 years 
theres no time limit now fmha spokeswoman marlyn aycock 
said wednesday no limit on the number of loans or on how many 
times you can come back for another loan 
the borrowing deadlines are part of an overall package of 
reforms the administration wants congress to approve for fmha an 
agriculture department agency which for many years has been known 
as the governments lender of last resort 
only those who have been denied loans by banks and other 
commercial institutions are eligible for fmha financing 
the proposal calls for a continued swing by the agency to 
guaranteed loans and away from direct fmha financing a trend that 
has prevailed for some years direct loans reached the 
billiondollar level in 1982 and then peaked at 47 billion in 
fiscal 1985 
for the last two years fmha direct farm operating loans have 
been around 900 million annually the bush budget proposed for the 
1991 fiscal year that will begin oct 1 includes 500 million for 
direct loans 
the administration also wants to restrict fmha direct operating 
loans to existing borrowers and to beginners who would become 
operators for the first time those could not have more than 
100000 in loans outstanding at any one time compared with the 
current limit of 200000 
meanwhile fmha guaranteed loan availability has risen from a 
negligible level in the early 1980s to 215 billion in 1988 and 
26 billion in 1989 
the administration also is seeking curbs on abuses under the 
agricultural credit act of 1987 including 250000 limits on debt 
writedowns and writeoffs there are no such limits now and some 
borrowers have had milliondollar writeoffs 
at a news conference announcing the administration proposals 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter said the fmha has tilted 
toward the grant side in recent years 
weve gone a long way from its original purposed of being a 
source of credit of last resort for farmers and youve got a whole 
variety of ways that have made it very nearly a grant program in 
many of it attributes he said the result of that is that it 
has cost the department and the american taxpayer a great deal of 
money 
the proposal for fmha also would tighten the direct farm 
ownership loan program by limiting new loans to socially 
disadvantaged applicants and impose a 150000 loan limit 
according to the proposal the 1987 credit act gave special 
emphasis to members of socially disadvantaged groups generally 
racial and ethnic minorities to provide an opportunity for them 
to buy farmland in the fmhas inventory of farms taken over from 
previous borrowers 
loan guarantees for those wishing to buy farms would be targeted 
to beginning farmers and those who wish to expand family holdings 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
one of the agriculture departments biggest 
annual surveys wil begin next week to see how farmers did 
financially in 1989 
charles caudill head of the departments national agricultural 
statistics service said the sixth annual farm costs and returns 
survey will begin feb 12 and run through march 30 
the agency is the departments primary gatherer of statistics 
used to compute farm income and expenses assets cash flow costs 
of production and other factors affecting the financial trends and 
general wellbeing of us agriculture 
about 26000 farms and ranches will be visited by local 
interviewers 
this survey goes directly to the source farmers themselves 
to develop an accurate picture of the diverse financial conditions 
in agriculture caudill said the costofproduction data help 
farm policymakers understand the costs of farming and ranching 
other information will help researchers analyze the financial 
situation in the farm sector how its changing and where problems 
are located he said results of the survey will be published by 
usda beginning this summer 
caudill said responses to survey questionnaires are 
confidential and all the forms are destroyed after the information 
is fed into computers and sent to agency headquarters in washington 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
payments to rice farmers who participated in 
the agriculture departments 1989 crop program total about 475 
million 
officials said about 225 million of the total in deficiency 
payments was paid in advance to rice producers upon request when 
they signed up in the program last year 
the departments agricultural stabilization and conservation 
service said the deficiency payment is based on the difference 
between the established target price and the higher of the national 
average price support rate or the national market price average 
received by producers in august through december 
for 1989 the payment will be 356 per 100 pounds the 
difference between last years target of 1080 and the market 
average of 724 
