<DOCNO> AP900208-0022 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the landmark 1986 tax overhaul is forcing 
americans to pay billions of dollars of taxes they had been 
evading but the law is getting low marks for simplification 
despite attempts at making things simpler says fred t goldberg 
jr commissioner of the internal revenue service the law is 
imposing an unacceptable burden on taxpayers and our system of 
tax administration he advised a new watchword do it simple 
rep bill archer of texas senior republican on the house ways 
and means committee told a hearing wednesday that as a lawyer and 
17year member of the panel he has always prided himself on doing 
his own tax return last year i could not do it he said 
for the most part however witnesses praised the impact of the 
new law the most thorough overhaul of the income tax since it was 
enacte in 1913 
goldberg ticked off several benefits 
the requirement that all children 4 and older since reduced to 
2 and older have social security numbers has brought in more than 
2 billion the requirement saw 7 million children dropped as 
dependents on tax returns research reflects the fact that those 
dependents never existed in the first place goldberg said 
repeal or reduction of several deductions generated billions 
of dollars in compliance revenues by removing the opportunity to 
overstate itemized deductions these changes caused more than 8 
million taxpayers to stop itemizing and resulted in tax increases 
for many despite the new laws reduction in tax rates 
tax reform 86 brought an end to the mass marketing of 
abusive tax shelters goldberg said an estimated 10 billion of 
partnership losses reported on 1987 returns were disallowed by the 
irs because of new rules 
while the bush administration was endorsing further 
simplification it also was repeating president bushs call for 
restoring a special break for capital gains a move that many 
experts say could bring even more complexity 
under the 1986 law capital gains which are profits from the 
sale of stock and other investments are fully taxed at the same 
rates applying to wages one of bushs top priorities is restoring 
that break on grounds it is needed to increase investment 
kenneth w gideon assistant secretary of the treasury for tax 
policy told the committee that despite gloomy predictions at the 
time the law was passed there is no clear evidence that the 1986 
act affected the level of investment one way or another 
the predicted shortrun decrease in aggregate equipment 
investment has apparently failed to materialize gideon said for 
whatever reason he added such investment has actually 
experienced a post1986act surge as a result of technologydriven 
increases and expenditures on office computing and accounting 
machinery and an increased growth in output demanded by other 
sectors of the economy 
rep dan rostenkowski dill chairman of the committee said 
deficit reduction is needed to improve the economy rather than 
enactment of special tax breaks 
among other judgments on the 1986 act 
the tradeoff of certain credits and deductions for lower 
statutory rates has had a positive effect on economic growth 
said harry sullivan senior vice president of the food marketing 
institute speaking for a coalition that includes 100 of the 
fortune 500 corporations 
while praising the law for removing 6 million lowerincome 
people from the tax rolls william lucy secretarytreasurer of the 
american federation of state county and municipal employees said 
its passage led many states into illadvised tax cuts resulting in 
reduced services for citizens 
representatives of the aerospace and petroleum industries said 
the law has put their businesses at a disadvantage 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

