sanctions and has given the administration discretionary authority 
to lift them if south africa meets four of the conditions that 
step would be automatic if all five are satisfied 
the senior administration official speaking to reporters on 
wednesday noted members of congress have argued strenuously 
against any early end to the sanctions 
he said until the time is ripe we dont dare lift the 
sanctions 
the official insisting on anonymity said that by legalizing 
the african national congress and other antiapartheid groups the 
south african government already has satisfied one of the 
conditions set by congress 
he added he expected south african compliance on three of the 
remaining four conditions government agreement to engage in good 
faith negotiations on the countrys political future the lifting 
of the state of emergency and the release of political prisoners 
the fifth condition requires substantial progress toward the 
dismantling of south africas apartheid system 
the official acknowledged there may be some ambiguity as to 
south african compliance with the conditions he said there may be 
disagreement for example over who is a political prisoner 
the sanctions were approved in 1986 over president reagans 
veto reagan argued approval of sanctions would lead to a loss of 
the us ability to influence south africa to ease its 
segregationist policies 
the sanctions include a ban on new investment in south africa a 
prohibition on the import of certain south african products and the 
cancellation of landing rights for south african airlines 
