<TEXT>
president bush criticized by 
environmentalists for his response on global warming faces new 
attacks on two other environmental issues protecting wetlands and 
cleaning up pollution on federal lands 
the national governors association released a report wednesday 
accusing the bush administration of hamstringing the environmental 
protection agency in attempts to pursue federal agencies that are 
violating pollution laws 
the nations chief environmental watchdog is forced to sit by 
as basic environmental statutes and regulations are routinely 
ignored at federally owned facilities said the report 
it said state authorities often are thwarted from action against 
federal sites by claims of national security 
the report by an nga task force cited a justice department 
policy which bars civil suits or enforcement actions against 
another federal agency on behalf of the epa 
idaho gov cecil andrus cochairman of the task force said 
bush could resolve the problem by one phone call to the epa and 
the justice department if you make a mess you clean it up were 
saying that goes for the federal government as well as private 
citizens the democratic governor said 
andrus said bush recognizes that there is widespread pollution 
on federal lands ranging from military bases to western grazing 
land held by the interior department but is proposing too little 
money to clean it up 
the epa lists 1268 federal facilities for priority cleanup 
efforts and that number is expected to grow for many years 
federal facilities have been among the worst violators of 
federal pollution laws said the governors report 
meanwhile environmentalists charged bush was retreating from a 
pledge to protect the nations wetlands they accused the 
administration of softening a policy position aimed at assuring 
that developers who exploit wetlands compensate for any 
environmental loss 
the criticism was prompted by a final agreement between the epa 
and the us army corps of engineers that outlines the procedures a 
developer must take and what compensation must be provided to 
develop a wetland area 
environmentalists hailed the position when it was tentatively 
agreed to last november but the document was revised during 
negotiations within the administration in recent weeks and 
environmentalists said the final version would allow developers in 
some cases to exploit wetlands without compensating for the 
environmental loss 
kathryn fuller president of the world wildlife fund and the 
conservation foundation said the revised agreement casts doubt on 
bushs promise to protect wetlands in the country 
the bush administration backed off from a strong position 
and has created one that is riddled with loopholes said robert 
irvin of the national wildlife federation 
the interagency agreement was negotiated for weeks by a number 
of federal agencies including the epa transportation department 
energy department and corps of engineers and white house chief of 
staff john sununu 
the white house was lobbied vigorously by oil companies and 
members of the alaska congressional delegation who argued that the 
original wetlands agreement might preclude drilling in vast areas 
of the states north slope tundra 
epa administrator william reilly reportedly argued for generally 
keeping the original document the epa announced a final decision 
without comment white house spokesmen have denied the revised 
document represents a change in the presidents commitment to 
protecting wetlands 
the energy department characterized the changes as providing 
needed flexibility to assure the development of petroleum and gas 
resources while protecting against further net loss of wetlands 
