portauprince haiti ap the countrys military rulers 
marked the fourth anniversary of dictator jeanclaude duvaliers 
fall by freeing 19 jailed opposition activists and promising to 
release all other political prisoners 
but opponents said the action wednesday did not mean democracy 
was on the way 
i consider i have left a small jail for a bigger one evans 
paul one of the released activists said in an interview broadcast 
by radio antilles the whole country is a prison 
the amnesty measure comes less than three weeks after the 
government of lt gen prosper avril declared a state of siege 
arrested many activists and sent several opposition leaders into 
exile 
several of those released wednesday were beaten while in prison 
including three who suffered serious head and body injuries fellow 
activists said four were jailed last year and most of the others 
were believed to have been arrested in a state of siege last month 
in a televised speech wednesday night avril announced a 
general amnesty of all those implicated in crimes against 
national security he urged haitians to respect the rules of 
the democratic game which he also promised to do 
the amnesty came exactly four years after baby doc 
duvaliers 1986 flight to exile in france following a popular 
uprising ending a 29year family dynasty in the impoverished 
carribean nation 
the government declared the day a paid national holiday 
a decree read on government tv after the speech said the amnesty 
covered all political prisoners jailed since avril seized power in 
september 1988 ousting lt gen henri namphy 
haitians around the world used the anniversary to protest and 
demand the ouster of avril there were demonstrations on the west 
indies islands of guadeloupe and martinique and in miami montreal 
and paris 
four of those freed three physicians and one artist were 
jailed after avril imposed a state of siege jan 20 they were 
released with head injuries broken ribs and bruises their 
families said 
following the state of siege more than 50 opposition activists 
and militants were arrested and beaten according to family members 
and friends seven others were exiled 
avril lifted the declaration after international outcry 
the other four men released are leaders of radical 
antigovernment groups and had been jailed since late last year 
they were jean auguste mesyeux marino etienne frantz patrick 
beauchard and paul 
paul said they were victims of arbitrary arrests and would 
sue 
mesyeux paul and etienne were arrested nov 1 and accused of 
possessing arms and explosives and of plotting to kill avril 
the sight of their battered faces on state tv a day after their 
arrest set off a storm of protests and strikes 
beauchard a former sergeant who helped bring avril to power 
was arrested dec 13 and accused of conspiring with mesyeux paul 
and etienne he was expelled from the army in late 1988 after avril 
accused him of plotting a countercoup 
press releases from the mens organizations said three suffered 
serious injuries they said paul may remain paralyzed on one 
side of his body that etienne may lose his right eye and has a 
broken ear drum and that mesyeux suffers from back pain and has 
problems walking due to pain on the bottom of his feet 
the three went on a 27day hunger strike during their 
imprisonment 
avril promised when he was brought to power in a soldiers 
revolt that unlike namphys regime his government would respect 
human rights but rights groups have denounced it for abuses 
a former close adviser to the duvalier regime avril has 
promised general elections for october but most organizations 
refuse to participate and many leaders are jailed or in exile 
the last time haiti attempted free elections in november 1987 
thugs protected by soldiers murdered at least 34 voters and the 
balloting was canceled 
robert duval president of the league of former political 
prisoners said recently that about 75 percent of the 340 murders 
in haiti last year were committed by soldiers duval has been 
hiding since jan 20 
