the commander of the us pacific command told 
congress wednesday that the united states should stop paying 
compensation to the philippines for two american bases 
adm huntington hardisty said he remains cautiously 
optimistic that the us and filipino governments can work out an 
agreement on clark air base and subic bay naval station before 
their leases expire next year 
philippines president corazon aquino who put down a coup 
attempt against her government in december is facing renewed 
pressure from top government officials not to extend the rights on 
the bases 
hardisty said the united states has contingency plans to move 
american forces in case usphilippines negotiations fail but the 
bases are ideal for the us effort in the pacific 
there is no single location or combination of locations that 
can replace what we now have in the philippines in terms of cost 
strategic positioning and operational efficiency hardisty told 
the house armed services committee 
the bush administration is requesting 200 million in fiscal 
1990 in payment to the philippines but congress is not expected to 
approve more than 160 million and hardisty said that was too much 
i feel were maxed out on compensation he told the 
committee in my opinion neither the congress nor the 
administration should vote for compensation weve got to be 
innovative and look at other ways other than paying rent 
