<TEXT>
the house is trying to ensure that legislation 
on oil spill liability require double hulls and double bottoms on 
tankers calling on us ports 
the house on wednesday approved 37637 a nonbinding 
resolution instructing negotiators to keep the provision in the 
bill that comes out of talks between the house and senate 
the provision is part of the bill passed the house but not in 
the senate version 
the housesenate conference committee is expected to begin work 
immediately on a compromise bill that both houses can approve 
before the march 24 anniversary of the exxonvaldez tanker spill in 
prince william sound alaska 
the vote on the resolution came before wednesdays major oil 
spill off a southern california beach 
a tanker off huntington beach calif struck an object under 
water spewing thousands of gallons of alaska crude oil from the 
american trader initial reports were that as much as 250000 
gallons of crude oil spilled making it the nations worst oil 
spill since the valdez 
the hull issue is viewed as the stickiest problem among the 
differences between the two bills the legislation which has taken 
14 years to get this far in congress is a comprehensive package of 
regulations laying out how oil spill cleanups should be managed 
and financed 
the hullbottom provision of the house bill requires tankers 
carrying oil and hazardous materials to be retrofitted with double 
bottoms within seven years of enactment and double hulls within 15 
years new tankers would have to be built with double hulls and 
double bottoms 
the senate version calls for a study to determine if any other 
technology would be an even better protection to the environment in 
case of a tanker accident 
</TEXT>
