<TEXT>
labor secretary elizabeth dole says she will 
toughen enforcement of child labor laws and seek higher fines for 
offenders 
the secretary said in a statement wednesday the department would 
review possible fines and would seek to take penalties to the 
highest level permissible under the law 
labor shortages in some areas in the future may put pressure on 
employers to hire young people and she said we want to make sure 
that employers follow the law to provide safe and rewarding work 
experiences 
mrs dole said she directed bill brooks assistant secretary for 
employment standards to develop a plan for targeted enforcement 
against egregious offenders and to recommend other changes 
in a speech to the departments child labor advisory committee 
brooks said child labor violations uncovered by the department 
of labor have more tha doubled since 1982 although tougher 
enforcement may explain some of the increase 
but labor shortages in certain areas have made it harder for 
businesses to find enough workers and some have responded by 
violating child labor laws he said in the remarks made available 
by the department 
brooks said the department would among other things 
step up efforts to increase public awareness of the law 
seek more injunctions against illegal acts 
propose better regulations for jobs which pose particular 
hazards for 16yearolds and 17yearolds 
generally those under 14 may work only in specific jobs exempt 
from the law the law and department regulations govern hours 
during which people under 16 may work and restrict employment in 
hazardous occupations for those under 18 different standards apply 
for farm labor 
