a czechoslovak diplomat said today that the 
kremlin is balking at a swift pullout of the estimated 75000 
soviet troops in czechoslovakia citing difficulties in absorbing 
the returning soldiers 
soviet and czechoslovak officials resumed negotiations today in 
moscow on the pullout which the new prague government wants 
completed by the end of the year 
antonin murgas a spokesman for the czechoslovak embassy in 
moscow said the soviets have argued that the deadline is 
impossible to meet for humanitarian reasons 
he said the soviet side contends such a pullout cannot begin 
until 1991 because there are not currently enough schools and homes 
in the soviet union for the families of the officers stationed in 
czechoslovakia 
czechoslovakias new noncommunist government led by president 
vaclav havel declared void two 1968 agreements with moscow that 
legalized the troops deployment 
the government which replaced hardline communists after a 
peaceful revolution in november not only demands all the troops 
out by the end of the year but wants half of the force out by may 
unlike hungary where initial talks on a soviet troop withdrawal 
took place last week czechoslovakia considers the matter of soviet 
troop withdrawal separate from vienna talks on arms reduction in 
europe 
the soviet forces in both countries are viewed as occupiers who 
crushed movements for democracy in hungary in 1956 and in 
czechoslovakia in 1968 
the demands from prague and budapest for a soviet troop pullout 
have increased pressure on moscow for a radical cutback in central 
europe under discussion at the vienna talks 
us secretary of state james a baker iii was in moscow today 
for talks on the us proposal to cut soviet and american troops in 
all of europe to 225000 on each side with a limit of 195000 in 
central europe 
