<TEXT>
packing 80 mph winds britains second major storm 
in two weeks felled trees disrupted transportation and brought 
rains that flooded homes and farmland police said the storm 
claimed two lives 
the atlantic storm hit wednesday lashing coastal towns and 
cities with southwesterly winds and disrupting ferry sailings in 
the english channel 
the winds and rain continued early today 
flooding shut down 25 miles of the a48 freeway in western 
england today gloucestershire police said 
british rail said rail links between perth and dundee in 
scotland and two routes in wales were closed today because of 
flooding fallen trees or damaged overhead power pickup lines on 
electrified sections of track 
police said a man died wednesday when a tree blown over by the 
wind crushed his car near andover 60 miles southwest of london 
a repairman trying to restore power to homes without electricity 
because of storm damage near warminster 95 miles west of london 
was also killed wednesday when he was struck by a car 
police said at least three people were injured in the storm 
the strong winds brought down power lines in southern england 
blacking out the small town of fleet 35 miles southwest of london 
and 2000 homes in surrounding countryside 
wales and the west country are particularly badly hit with 
flooding and very high winds making conditions absolutely 
unbearable a spokesman for the automobile association said 
weather forecasting organizations have been scrupulous about 
predicting storms since an october 1987 nighttime storm that took 
much of southern england by surprise killing 20 people a defense 
ministry investigation said the meteorological office failed to 
give adequate warning of that storm because its scientists put too 
much trust in the predictions of an outofdate computer 
a storm that struck europe on jan 25 killed 47 people in 
britain and caused 17 billion in damage 
forecasters said the high winds are caused by cold air moving 
down from the arctic hitting unseasonably warm air surrounding 
britain in the atlantic creating the very dramatic low pressure 
that fuels the winds 
