china today declared it would not accept wanton 
attacks on its human rights record by the united states and said 
a state department report on the issue would do further serious 
harm to sinous relations 
foreign ministry spokesman jin guihua at a weekly briefing 
also dismissed as utterly groundless charges of widespread 
human rights violations by the usbased human rights organization 
asia watch 
the annual state department human rights report has yet to be 
released but congressional sources in washington say it harshly 
criticizes china 
it reportedly chronicles the continued political use of 
executions suppression of labor rights slave labor camps in 
western china and religious persecution of catholics and buddhists 
jin said he had not seen the report but we are resolutely 
opposed to the imposition of ones own values on others by any 
country and interference in chinas internal affairs under the 
pretext of human rights 
he added should the us state department insist on its 
wanton attacks against china in its human rights report which is 
based on rumors and which is to be released soon it will certainly 
do further serious harm to sinous relations and will arouse 
greater indignation from the chinese people 
he said the asia watch report released wednesday which accuses 
china of continued arrests and secret executions of people involved 
in the crushed prodemocracy movement was utterly groundless and 
with ulterior motives 
the chinese government attaches importance to human rights 
he said and the fact that some individuals are dealt with 
according to law because they have breached the criminal law is 
just for the purpose of protecting the human rights of the broad 
masses 
he said the chinese government has stated that participants of 
the prodemocracy demonstations last spring who did not violate 
criminal law would not be prosecuted 
the asia watch report said tens of thousands of dissenters are 
languishing in chinese jails many are denied access to lawyers and 
are subject to physical and mental torture it said 
the report criticized president bush for moving to improve 
relations with china while human rights violations remain pervasive 
