<TEXT>
a teenage girl died four days after 
becoming the worlds first recipient of an experimental lung 
device leaving behind a newborn son and a grieving hometown but 
hope that similar implants will save lives 
melicia mimi harvey 16 of arthur city texas who suffered 
from respiratory distress syndrome died wednesday of pulmonary 
failure said tim madden spokesman at lds hospital 
mimi had received an intravascular oxygenator or ivox in a 
twohour operation friday the device which works like a lung is 
a 20inch bundle of hundreds of synthetic tubes as fine as human 
hair with walls so thin that oxygen and carbon dioxide can pass 
through 
there were no clinical complications from the use of the 
device madden said 
lds and three other medical centers have federal approval to 
implant the device in up to 10 patients and dr jd mortensen 
chief developer of the ivox for cardiopulmonics inc of salt lake 
city said the implants will continue 
it will take a long time to review the mountain of data we 
gathered with this case from what we know with this case it was 
extremely successful mortensen said 
nevertheless he said nine of the 10 patients who will receive 
the device are expected to die 
word of mimis death stunned classmates at frank stone high 
school in paris texas a month before mimi died she gave birth to 
a son trenell mimis mother edith harvey 41 died jan 31 of 
diabetesrelated causes 
many of the schools 735 students who included the girls 
