prosecutors thursday ordered the release of 
80 moslem fundamentalists detained for nearly two months on charges 
of illegal possession of weapons and antigovernment activities 
abdelaziz mokhtar the citys chief prosecutor cited lack of 
evidence as the reason 
the charges against the detainees all university students 
stemmed from a battle dec 11 between police and more than 300 
moslem militants who tried to march from a mosque to the city 
center in an antigovernment demonstration 
the clash left 10 policemen and 30 militants wounded many by 
bullets assiut 238 miles south of cairo has been a center of 
fundamentalist agitation in recent years 
at least 500 people were arrested soon after the demonstration 
all were gradually released except the 80 who were remanded to 
custody by government prosecutors investigating the case 
the detainees were charged with resisting authorities illegal 
possession of arms and explosives and unlawful assembly 
about 10 other moslem militants remain in jail in connection 
with a clash last month with police during a demonstration outside 
a mosque one militant was killed reportedly by police gunfire 
