<TEXT>
british and argentine officials opened two 
days of talks thursday on issues related to the disputed falkland 
islands a step toward restoring full diplomatic ties embassy 
spokesmen said 
an argentine embassy official who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said argentina would ask britain to drop the 150mile 
military protection zone around the falklands which argentina 
calls the malvinas islands 
the zone has been enforced since argentina invaded the south 
atlantic islands in 1982 the argentine soldiers were driven off by 
british troops after a 74day war 
britain now requires argentine military ships to request and 
receive british permission before entering the zone 
the talks thursday were held at the argentine ambassadors 
residence in central madrid on friday the talks will move across 
the street to the british embassy 
a british embassy spokesman said details of the meetings were 
not expected to be made public 
the talks serve as a preliminary step to highlevel meetings in 
madrid on feb 1415 that will be aimed at restoring full 
diplomatic relations 
argentina has claimed the islands since declaring independence 
from spain in 1816 british claims to the islands are based on 
effective occupation since 1833 
relations between the two countries have improved considerably 
since october when two days of talks in madrid ended with the 
restoration of consular relations and an agreement to move toward 
normal diplomatic and economic relations 
since then argentina has allowed british vessels and planes to 
operate freely in argentine territory and britain has lifted a 
restriction on the navigation of argentine merchant ships in the 
150mile military protection zone around the falklands 
britains fiveman delegation at this weeks talks was led by 
adrian beamish the foreign offices assistant undersecretary of 
state for the americas 
the argentine side was headed by jose maria otegui 
directorgeneral for the malvinas 
</TEXT>
