<TEXT>
prime minister ingvar carlsson said 
thursday the economy is falling apart and his government will 
resign unless parliament bans strikes and imposes a wageprice 
freeze for two years 
the plan that finance minister kjellolof feldt outlined in 
parliament also would put a twoyear freeze on local taxes rents 
and stock dividends 
some opposition legislators accused carlssons social democrats 
of declaring economic martial law and advocating a planned economy 
when eastern europe is abandoning that approach 
a vote is expected next week on the plan which is designed to 
curb rapidly rising wages and annual inflation of 86 percent 
twice the west european average 
carlssons minority government needs the support of at least one 
opposition party to pass each of its proposals both conservatives 
and liberals have indicated they would support a tax freeze and 
the communists said they would go along with freezing prices rents 
and stock earnings 
if parliament rejects our demands the government cannot stay 
on carlsson told a news conference we will not administer an 
economy that is falling apart 
his plan would suspend a 50yearold agreement under which 
powerful unions and employers associations negotiate wages 
quietly without government intervention 
collective bargaining is a pillar of the swedish welfare system 
which has eliminated poverty and guaranteed health care and 
education for everyone the swedish mix of socialism and capitalism 
became a model for the industrial welfare state 
what was known as the swedish model is on the whole gone 
and this is just another sign bank economist nils lundgren said 
on swedish radio 
strikes would be prohibited for the duration of the plan 
through 1991 and a striker could be fined 5000 kronor about 800 
to help curb absenteeism and cheating on sick leave the 
government would stop paying salaries for the first two weeks of 
illness shifting the burden to the employer under current rules 
the government pays sick leave from the first day 
what we propose is without doubt an austere policy feldt 
said it also means an important deviation from the swedish model 
of free wage negotiations but it is necessary 
carlsson said to make the wage freeze work it must be 
combined with a strike freeze if the riksdag parliament takes 
the package to pieces the package is meaningless 
approval of the plan would preempt a strike by 110000 municipal 
employees called for wednesday that would halt public 
transportation public health services and daycare in major cities 
banks have been closed for 11 days since 62000 employees were 
locked out after a deadlock in wage negotiations people are 
strapped for cash the stock market is virtually inoperative and 
some companies soon may be unable to pay salaries and bills 
if this merrygoround isnt stopped it could lead to anarchy 
on the labor market feldt said 
he compared the labor strife with britains winter of 
discontent in 1979 when strikes caused a conservative backlash 
that put prime minister margaret thatcher in power 
swedens largest union known as lo expressed guarded approval 
of the plan union president stig malm a member of the social 
democratic leadership said many members would be unhappy about the 
wage freeze but expressed hope the package as a whole would win 
great understanding 
sture nord of tco a whitecollar union declared in 
disagreement we cannot accept limits of trade unions rights 
carlsson told the news conference sweden was pricing itself out 
of the european market through rising production costs 
we had hoped the trade unions and employers organizations 
would agree on a lower cost development to increase competitive 
strength and reduce inflation he said they did not 
in parliament feldt said sweden is rushing into a cost 
crisis and that cannot be permitted 
