<TEXT>
fort bragg enlisted a psychologist to 
help soldiers deal with their feelings about combat in panama in 
the armys first attempt to prevent posttraumatic stress disorder 
before it appears 
we called it shell shock in world war ii lt col dick 
bridges an army spokesman at the pentagon said wednesday in a 
telephone interview but weve come to understand it better and 
have only called it posttraumatic stress since 1980 
bridges said he wasnt sure if the army provided counseling for 
the disorder after the invasion of grenada in october 1983 but 
it seems to me that this is the first time that weve tried to be 
proactive in trying to treat it before it happens 
unlike vietnam veterans soldiers returning from panama were 
greeted by cheers and commendations and psychologists say that 
could make them less likely to suffer the effects of posttraumatic 
stress disorder 
last week bragg invited some psychologists to work with 
soldiers and their family members who were involved with the panama 
incursion dubbed operation just cause said maj doug foster base 
spokesman the medical community at womack army community hospital 
worked with the psychologists to learn to recognize early symptoms 
of the syndrome he said 
dr tom williams a consultant for the post trauma treatment 
center at centennial peaks hospital in louisville colo spent 
five days at fort bragg on a volunteer basis and spoke to about 
2000 soldiers and family members 
williams said he drew on his own experiences as a marine captain 
during two tours in vietnam to help soldiers at fort bragg cope 
with their feelings after their brief combat experience 
im jealous because these guys went in as a unit and came out 
as a unit said williams 38 i didnt have that luxury in 
vietnam nobody cared about us afterwards either in the defense 
department or the civilian community 
the brief duration of the fighting in panama which ended in the 
first week after the initial assault does not prevent the 
possibility of emotional ill effects he said 
what we would not want to see is what happened after vietnam 
high states of depression high suicide rates high alcoholism 
rates and high divorce rates williams said 
if we were talking about an airplane crash and people who 
pulled bodies out and risked their lives in recovering survivors 
there would be no question there would be emotional response to 
that williams said combatants have the same type of response 
because theyre human beings 
the effects of traumatic events go beyond the mind williams 
said 
were talking about the endocrine system bursts of adrenalin 
which our body has for our survival he said when adrenalin 
gets used up then you have another chemical which slows down all 
the body processes particularly the nervous system thus the 
listlessness 
no one seems able to escape the effects of going into battle 
not even the soldiers left behind 
the people who stayed in the rear have to realize what they 
did was important williams said 
understanding can ease the way for soldiers who may experience 
trauma from the ordeal 
family members must realize that experiencing combat either 
firsthand or indirectly inevitably alters the life of their loved 
one williams said a soldiers homecoming is easier if 
families understand the typical emotional responses one has 
experienced 
