<TEXT>
the federal communications commission on 
thursday ordered a record 14 million fine against new york 
telephone co and new england telephone and telegraph co for 
alleged improper dealings with an affiliated company and ordered 
them to refund about 35 million to customers 
the fine against the two subsidiaries of nynex corp was the 
maximum allowed under current law and involved alleged 1185 
million in overcharges made to nyt and net by material enterprises 
co an unregulated nynex affiliate nynex established in 1983 to 
provide equipment and services to the two phone companies 
the action the largest federal penalty ever imposed on a 
telephone company was seen as a tough warning to the nations 
huge regional bell companies that the fcc is committed to 
regulating the multibilliontelephone industry 
critics claim the fcc cannot effectively regulate the giant hone 
companies particularly if congress bows to the phone companies 
requests that they be freed from federal rules that bar them from 
the manufacturing information services and longdistance 
businesses 
fcc chairman alfred sikes told reporters the fccs action 
demonstrates the commissions capability and commitment to 
regulate even the largest telephone companies 
sikes said the benefits to be derived from improved competition 
and diversification in the phone industry following the 1984 
breakup of the bell system must be accompanied by strong 
ratepayer and competitive safeguards todays action demonstrates 
that such safeguards actually exist and that they are being 
efficiently administered and vigorously enforced 
nynex has 30 days to answer the fccs order and company 
officials said they would state their case strongly 
nyt and net each were fined 709500 nynex has revenues of 
about 12 billion annually 
richard firestone the fccs chief telephone regulator defended 
the size of the fine as the maximum penalty available under the 
rules 
he said the companies were being penalized because we dont 
believe this was an inadvertent error in bookkeeping 
nynex chairman william ferguson said the company welcomed the 
fcc audit so that nynexs arguments finally will be heard in a case 
that first was disclosed by the boston globe 
but ferguson said the fcc was incorrectly subjecting nynex to 
rules that were established in 1977 for atampt and its affiliate the 
western electric co 
ferguson also maintained that nynex had scrupulously followed 
1987 fcc bookkeeping safeguards designed to prevent costshifting 
to nonregulated affiliates and that nynex had agreed with new york 
state regulators to turn over ownership of meco to the two phone 
companies 
my overriding concern is our customers and the good faith of 
our customers because certainly there has been no intention to 
overcharge ferguson said 
new york state regulators and new york telephone officials 
recently reached a settlement under which nyt would reduce a 900 
million rate hike request to a 367 million cut this year and an 
increase of 445 million in 1991 with another 20 million to be 
used to make up for any overcharges by meco 
as part of the agreement state officials would end their 
investigation of nynex and meco 
a new york judge on tuesday rejected the settlement as being 
inadequate 
thursdays fcc order was based on the findings of a routine 
audit initiated during 1988 firestone said audit would have taken 
place despite the the boston globe reports but that the news 
stories did cause fcc auditors to shift their attack 
the bureau audit focused on compliance with the affiliate 
transaction rules and policies which are designed to protect 
ratepayers and competition from harmful crosssubsidies the fcc 
said 
the rules provide that when a regulated telephone company such 
as nyt or net purchases supplies or services from an affiliated 
company the telephone company may recover from ratepayers no more 
than the cost that would have been incurred in an arms length 
transaction 
the fcc said the three companies engaged in a series of 
transactions between 1984 and 1988 designed to increase the overall 
profits of their parent company nynex corp at ratepayer expense 
the fcc said its audit revealed that nyt and net purchased 
equipment supplies and services from meco at prices that were 
inflated by 1185 million approximately 35 million of these 
inflated costs were passed along to interstate ratepayers the fcc 
said 
firestone said about 97 percent of mecos business was with 
nynex 
thursdays action will not affect local telephone rates for nyt 
and net customers any refunds would have to be made through a 
reduction in the fees longdistance carriers such as atampt pay to 
connect with the local telephone company networks 
when the longdistance companies pay lower access fees they 
must pass those savings along to customers 
</TEXT>
