<TEXT>
the federal communications commission on 
thursday ordered fines totaling 14 million against new york 
telephone co and new england telephone and telegraph co for 
allegedly improper dealings with an affiliated company and ordered 
them to refund about 35 million to customers 
the fine against the two subsidiaries of nynex corp was the 
largest federal penalty ever imposed on a telephone company and 
involved alleged 1185 million in overcharges made to new york 
telephone and new england telephone by material enterprises co an 
unregulated nynex affiliate established in 1983 to provide 
equipment and services to the two phone companies 
nynex has 30 days to answer the fccs order company officials 
said they would state their case strongly 
the action the maximum allowed under law was seen as a tough 
warning to the nations huge regional bell companies that the fcc 
is committed to regulating the multibilliontelephone industry 
critics claim the fcc cannot effectively regulate the giant 
phone companies particularly if congress bows to the companies 
requests that they be freed from federal rules barring them from 
the manufacturing information services and longdistance 
businesses 
fcc chairman alfred sikes told reporters the fccs action 
demonstrates the commissions capability and commitment to 
regulate even the largest telephone companies 
new york telephone and new england telephone each were fined 
709500 nynex has revenues of about 12 billion annually 
richard firestone the fccs chief telephone regulator said the 
companies were being penalized because we dont believe this was 
an inadvertent error in bookkeeping 
nynex chairman william ferguson said the company welcomed the 
fcc audit so that nynexs arguments finally will be heard in a case 
that first was disclosed by the boston globe 
but ferguson said the fcc was incorrectly subjecting nynex to 
rules that were established in 1977 for atampt and its affiliate the 
western electric co 
ferguson also maintained that nynex had scrupulously followed 
1987 fcc bookkeeping standards designed to prevent costshifting to 
nonregulated affiliates and that nynex had agreed with new york 
state regulators to turn over ownership of material enterprises to 
the two phone companies 
my overriding concern is our customers and the good faith of 
our customers because certainly there has been no intention to 
overcharge ferguson said 
the fcc said the three companies engaged in a series of 
transactions from 1984 to 1988 designed to increase the overall 
profits of nynex at customer expense 
the fcc said its audit revealed that new york telephone and new 
england telephone purchased equipment supplies and services from 
material enterprises at prices that were inflated by 1185 
million approximately 35 million of these inflated costs were 
passed along to interstate customers the fcc said 
thursdays action will not affect local telephone rates for new 
york telephone and new england telephone customers refunds would 
have to be made through a reduction in the fees longdistance 
carriers such as atampt pay to connect with the local telephone 
company networks 
when the longdistance companies pay lower access fees they 
must pass those savings along to customers 
</TEXT>
