<TEXT>
the federal communications commission on 
thursday proposed new regulations aimed at making it easier for 
wireless cable television systems to compete with their wired 
counterparts 
the commission which is bent on improving competition in a 
cable tv industry beset by complaints of rate increases and poor 
service voted 40 to consider eliminating multiple ownership 
restrictions on microwave radio channels used by wireless cable 
systems increase permissible power output establish new 
interference requirements and improve wireless cables access to 
underused frequencies 
those and other proposed changes plus streamlined applications 
would help wireless cable become a competitive spur to wired 
cable system operators the fcc said 
the commissions notice inviting public comment said most of 
the rules at issue were adopted in the infancy of the various 
services they govern and did not anticipate the potential of a 
wireless cable service to compete in todays multichannel video 
marketplace 
many existing rules the fcc said are now individually 
inappropriate and also are inconsistent from service to service 
the fcc also said it would consider reallocating to wireless 
cable some frequencies now reserved for instructional television 
and other private services 
fcc commissioner sherrie marshall said the proposed changes were 
part of an effort to create a level playing field between wired 
and wireless cable 
wireless cable uses microwave radio instead of coaxial cable 
to reach its customers microwave radio beams signals from one 
point to another unlike ordinary overtheair broadcasting which 
spreads in all directions using longer wavelengths these microwave 
links must be licensed by the fcc 
wireless cable systems usually combine standard tv broadcast 
receiving equipment with special microwave equipment to provide 
nonbroadcast and broadcast signals to homes schools apartment 
buildings and businesses not wired for coaxial cable 
wireless cable systems claim they cant compete effectively with 
wired cable systems because they lack large channel capacity and 
because cable tv programmers such as home box office refuse to give 
them programs at fair prices accusations that hbo denies 
robert l schmidt president of the wireless cable association 
said the commissions decision was a positive step toward 
assuring that wireless cable is a viable competitor 
but schmidt said the commissions actions did not address the 
fundamental problem impeding the wireless cable industry 
restricted availability of fairly priced programming 
schmidt said he hoped some of these problems would be resolved 
in two inquiries into the cable tv business the fcc is expected to 
finish by summer 
in other actions thursday the commission voted 40 to 
propose creation of an entrylevel communicator class of 
amateur radio license that would not require ham operators to know 
morse code the commission said it wanted to open amateur radio to 
young technically oriented people who dont want to learn morse 
code 
streamline the application process for am radio license 
applications and changes 
propose additional channels for mobilesatellite radio services 
 
