<TEXT>
federal officials should attack the 300 
billion business of laundering drug money with steps ranging from a 
banking summit to supermarketstyle bar codes on 20 bills a 
senator said thursday 
we hope that the administration will get off the dime and get 
moving on this sen john kerry dmass told a news conference 
at which he released a wideranging report on the laundering of 
proceeds of drug sales 
he recommended a summit between top bankers and officials of the 
state and treasury departments aimed at speeding action he also 
called on the senate banking committee to launch an investigation 
of the laundering of cash missing as part of the savings and loan 
industry crisis 
kerry called for aggressive pursuit of information from foreign 
banks backed up by the threat of real sanctions adding that 
officials should look hard at allowing banks to keep part of 
any laundered money found 
banks should be required to know their customers and real names 
not aliases should be required on checks kerry said he said 
there should be federal requirements for check cashing operations 
such as currency exchanges 
some recovered money should be funneled into the effort to 
combat crime in highintensity drug areas he said and money 
should be stamped with bar codes that would allow computerized 
tracking of the flow of currency 
the report based on testimony last fall before the senate 
foreign relations and banking committees quoted assistant treasury 
secretary salvatore martoche as estimating that drug revenues total 
300 billion annually including 110 billion generated in the 
united states 
it said much of the money laundered worldwide comes from 
criminal activities other than drug sales such as loan sharking 
but that narcotics represents a major portion laundering is not 
always simple it said 
for example 100 billion in 20 bills a denomination often 
used in drug transactions would weigh 26 million pounds the 
report said 
a money laundering operation in new york shut down earlier 
this year required a tractortrailer to haul away 19 million in 
small bills it said 
the report said the 1970 bank secrecy act is working as a 
deterrent to money laundering through american financial 
institutions the measure requires the institutions to report cash 
deposits of 10000 or more 
however the report said that drug traffickers continue to use 
foreign banks and foreign branches of us banks to launder us 
drug profits 
switzerland canada the bahamas luxembourg panama and hong 
kong are among the main countries where money is laundered the 
report said adding that criminals are pushing to develop money 
laundering centers in a number of tiny countries ranging from 
andorra to vanuatu 
the report said the government has no policy on control of 
international electronic transfers of us funds 
as a consequence money launderers retain a choice of methods 
to conceal their laundered funds through international wire 
transfers including informal channels involving fax machines 
telex personal computer networks and ordinary telephone 
instructions which do not leave the paper trail which would allow 
investigators to follow the flow of funds it said 
