<TEXT>
the federal communications commission on 
thursday upheld a review boards decision that stripped from san 
francisco station kqedtv its license to operate a uhf educational 
station kqec 
the review board had ruled kqed failed to deal honestly with the 
commission 
the fcc said it will award a new license to the minority 
television project inc for a new station using kqec facilities 
provided that minority television project supplies proof it has 
received sufficient state and federal funds 
the commission said it agreed with the review boards conclusion 
that kqed officials committed serious misconduct by lacking 
candor about and misrepresenting the reasons that kqec was off the 
air from january through may 1980 
it said the record showed kqeds board of directors adopted a 
resolution authorizing the deactivation of kqec channel 32 as a 
means of alleviating kqeds financial problems 
the commission said that on three occasions after the resolution 
was adopted kqed told the commission the uhf station was closed 
for technical reasons associated with the replacement of switcher 
equipment and did not disclose the boards decision 
the commission said that it had warned kqed in 1975 that it 
considered kqeds practice of deactivating channel 32 for financial 
reasons contrary to the public interest 
the commission said that even after it learned of the boards 
resolution as the result of a complaint kqed attempted to 
characterize its action as related to the switcher replacement and 
not a general budgetary matter such conduct violates the 
fundamental duty of a licensee to deal honestly with the 
commission 
despite kqeds misconduct the commission said it was upholding 
the review boards decision to renew the license of kqedtv and 
kqedfm 
the board found that kqed did not commit the kind of pervasive 
misconduct that would have disqualified kqed from holding any 
broadcast licenses and that the loss of a single station was the 
appropriate sanction in view of the misconduct committed 
kqed may continue operating kqec for 90 days if kqed seeks 
reconsideration of the fcc order or judicial review it may 
continue to operate the station for 90 days following release of 
any reconsideration order or the completion of judicial review 
whichever is later 
</TEXT>
