a leading government official said 
thursday that albania will remain unaffected by democratic reforms 
sweeping the soviet bloc but welcomes the superpowers reduced 
role in europe 
we are continuing along our own road which has been very 
different from that of the eastern bloc countries deputy foreign 
minster socrat placa told the associated press 
albania is europes last bastion of stalinism 
it is rare here that officials consent to comment spontaneously 
and on the record to western reporters this small mountainous 
nation between greece and yugoslavia is a closed society that for 
decades has been europes most conservative communist nation 
the tirana government broke with the soviet union in 1961 over 
moscows policy of destalinization and with china in 1978 because 
it viewed beijing as deviating from marxistleninist tenets 
placa said albania followed european developments with intense 
interest and welcomed any reductions of usled nato and 
sovietled warsaw pact forces from the continent the two sides are 
making progress at talks in vienna on cutting their conventional 
troop strengths 
although it takes part in few international forums and restricts 
entry by foreigners albania consistently denies being isolationist 
in arguing against the isolationist label placa used as an 
example albanias not participating in the helsinki process of 
building intereuropean trust and reducing the threat of military 
confrontation on the continent 
we have not been involved in international politics for 
example the helsinki process because that did not respect the will 
of the nations involved simply the interests of the power 
blocs he said 
albania now has diplomatic relations with 112 countries many 
of them nonaligned third world nations and placa said his country 
was interested in improving our diplomatic links both with the 
east and west 
asked about albanias relationship with the united states placa 
blamed the americans for the lack of formal ties 
it was not our making that we are not engaged in diplomatic 
relations with america really the ball is in their court 
he said 
he did not elaborate on consistent rejections by his government 
of such relations with both superpowers 
placa repeated albanian rejections of the reform process 
gripping much of eastern europe saying the turmoil has been 
due to misguided socialism bureaucracy and corruption 
we do not have that here he said 
despite militant rhetoric signs have been emerging that albania 
is slightly relaxing decades of dogma as part of a cautious move 
away from total control of society by the ruling communist party 
the state ata news agency reported sunday that a central 
committee meeting on jan 2223 agreed to give state enterprises 
more decisionmaking power permit dual candidacies and tie wages 
more closely to production 
such moves are sorely needed but will not likely be nearly 
enough to inject competition into a rigid centrally controlled 
economy that draws on an infrastructure that has changed little 
since the early 1950s 
albania has the lowest gross national product in europe 
estimated at 820 a year per capita by the world bank in 1981 the 
last year statistics were available it has about 31 million 
residents 
foreign business people said albania wants badly to increase its 
foreign trade currently a paltry 860000 a year 
the potential is there but this country has a lot to do 
before it becomes an attractive prospect said kurt felbsberger 
an italian tourism promoter on his first visit 
the bottom line here is they dont have the money to pay for 
the goods they want bartering which they would like to see is an 
antiquated form of trade said a finnish foreign trade official 
who spoke on the condition of anonymity 
placa told western reporters that nothing stood in the way of 
economic cooperation with the rest of europe 
there are no obstacles to increased trade and we should not be 
afraid of joint ventures he said without elaborating 
the moribund economy and resulting food shortages acknowledged 
by ata in its feb 4 report were reported partially responsible 
for riots said to have occurred in the northern city of skhoder 
jan 11 and jan 14 the violence reportedly was associated with 
anticommunist rallies there 
but placa said such reports were simply fabricated 
propaganda mainly by yugoslav statesupervised media 
albania and yugoslavias federal government are at odds over the 
fate of 19 million ethnic albanians in the yugoslav province of 
kosovo more than 25 ethnic albanians died there in the latest wave 
of unrest for more autonomy 
