two female helicopter pilots rushing us 
troops to attack zones came under heavy fire during the panamanian 
invasion the pilots said thursday providing new evidence of the 
exposure of army women to combat during the operation 
one pilots helicopter had to be grounded after it was hit 
at night when you see the tracer bullets coming at you you 
realize you could end up giving up your life for your country 
said one of the women army lt lisa kutschera of milwaukee 
the pilots story is a new indication of the combatarea roles 
women played during the attack roles that have sparked 
controversy over what military women should or shouldnt be allowed 
to do in the future 
kutschera along with warrant officer debra mann flew uh60 
blackhawk helicopters trying to evade enemy bullets as they 
ferried infantry troops to several landing zones between midnight 
and dawn of dec 20 
after mann returned from one flight it was discovered that her 
helicopter had been hit by several rounds and damaged badly enough 
to ground it 
wed heard the shots but we didnt even know we had been 
hit she said in an interview by telephone from panama 
the two women along with a third female pilot who also faced 
gunfire during a supply flight the next day have been nominated 
for the air medal 
kutschera and mann also have been nominated to receive the 
additional v designating valor device on the medal for 
particular courage they would be the first women to get the v 
us law bars the navy and air force from placing women in 
combat roles the army attempts to follow the law with its policy 
of combat exclusion that prevents women from being assigned 
jobs directly related to combat as the army defines it that is 
seeking out and engaging the enemy 
since kutschera and mann were ferrying troops in and out of 
battle zones by helicopter and not piloting attack helicopters 
