<TEXT>
the sanctions congress imposed against south 
africa in 1986 took a stiff economic and psychological toll on the 
white government and helped encourage reforms a wide spectrum of 
experts say 
international trade sanctions alone have probably resulted in 
a 2 billion loss annually to the south african economy said 
stephen r lewis jr author of the economics of apartheid 
but lewis president of carlton college in northfield minn 
said us sanctions probably had a greater psychological than 
quantitative impact on south africa because washington never played 
a dominant role in the countrys economy 
fewer than 1 percent of all south africans are employed by 
american companies 
as a result of sanctions however the south african government 
could no longer kid itself the united states would come down on 
its side lewis said 
congress he said sent a message that us opposition to 
apartheid was broadbased not simply a domestic political issue 
driven by the black community 
still the us sanctions combined with an international oil 
boycott other countries restrictions and the inefficiencies of 
apartheid have devastated the economy of south africa a country 
rich in gold and minerals several scholars said 
south africas economy has grown at less than 2 percent in 
recent years compared with about 5 percent between 19501970 
lewis said there is high black unemployment a 20 billion 
external debt and a loss of business confidence 
i think sanctions were quite important said pauline baker 
of the carnegie endowment for international peace a think tank 
they finally made an impact on whites the economy was in 
irreversible decline 
michael johns an analyst at the heritage foundation a 
conservative think tank agreed that sanctions have had a negative 
effect on south africa at this point there has been a 
realization sanctions played a role and increased the pressure 
on south africa 
as important as sanctions in influencing south africa johns 
said were the winds of change blowing through eastern europe 
and other parts of the world conservatives were generally against 
sanctions 
rep dan burton rind a longtime opponent of sanctions 
agreed that they hurt the government but he said he opposed them 
because i have felt for some time the people who suffered most 
were the blacks 
he said positive change could have been brought about just as 
rapidly through creating educational health and jobs programs 
for blacks 
the reagan administration along with thenvice president george 
bush opposed sanctions but assistant secretary of state herman j 
cohen said last year that sanctions have had a positive effect 
according to a paper on sanctions prepared by the house foreign 
affairs committee 
among other things us sanctions barred new us investment 
including bank loans to the south african government prohibited 
the import of south african iron steel coal and uranium and 
agricultural products including sugar prevented the united states 
from exporting computers to south africa banned all nuclear trade 
and halted landings by south african airways 
in general sanctions have helped persuade whites inside the 
country they cant conduct business as usual said steven davis 
a senior analyst at the investor responsibility research center a 
group that monitors activity in south africa 
davis said the number of american companies doing business in 
south africa is about 123 down from a onetime high of 300 
a top administration official said wednesday that south africa 
is likely to make enough progress in easing oppression against 
blacks over the next year to permit lifting of us sanctions 
but despite south african president fw de klerks recent 
loosening of some apartheid regulations several members of 
congress said it would be premature to repeal sanctions because not 
all conditions for their removal have been met 
this is a time when the united states can do the most good by 
waiting and watching said sen richard lugar rind 
as chairman of the senate foreign relations committee in 1986 
lugar supported sanctions against south africa leading the drive 
to override president reagans veto of the comprehensive 
antiapartheid act 
apartheid remains intact despite de klerks steps several 
lawmakers said 
de klerk legalized the african national congress after three 
decades of guerrilla war against white rule and said he would soon 
free nelson mandela the anc leader mprisoned in 1962 
de klerks actions important as they are do not meet all the 
conditions required to build the appropriate prenegotiations 
climate said rep howard wolpe dmich chairman of the house 
africa subcommittee 
nor to they meet the conditions set down in us law required 
to lift the american sanctions he said 
wolpes committee along with a house banking subcommittee will 
hold hearings later this month on legislation that would prohibit 
banks from rescheduling any debt held by south africa 
the sanctions dictate that de klerk release all political 
prisoners end the state of emergency completely and allow all 
political parties to operate 
president bush said he wants to review us policy toward south 
africa including the sanctions 
