<TEXT>
officials and environmentalists on thursday 
likened the huntington beach oil spill to a rude wakeup call and 
urged lawmakers to pass tough legislation to protect fragile 
shorelines and punish polluters 
once again dumb luck has smiled on california every good 
break we could have gotten we have state controller gray davis 
told a news conference in huntington beach after a helicopter tour 
over the slick off the coast 
wednesdays 295000gallon oil spill from the tanker american 
trader threatened miles of beaches and estuaries thursday but 
favorable offshore winds held the slick stationary against an 
onshore current a mile out to sea and calm seas eased cleanup 
efforts later however the wind reversed direction 
davis who sits on the california lands commission promised a 
state investigation 
he also said the commission would call on congress to require 
tankers be fitted with double hulls an issue now before congress 
the commission which regulates oil development in state lands 
and waters declared previously unprotected tracts in state waters 
offlimits to new drilling in december 
this serves as a wakeup call lt gov leo mccarthy said at 
the news conference he urged the state assembly to pass pending 
oil spill prevention and liability legislation 
attorney general john van de kamp speaking to reporters on the 
beach a short time later called the spill a very fortuitous 
beneficial warning to state residents and lawmakers 
we need to do something to make sure this doesnt happen 
again said van de kamp a democratic candidate for governor 
a us housesenate conference committee is working on differing 
house and senate bills to produce a measure both chambers can 
approve by the march 24 anniversary of the exxon valdez spill in 
alaskas prince william sound 
davis and mccarthy cited the spill in pushing for passage of a 
state bill that would require tankers be equipped with booms and 
other cleanup equipment 
the bill would establish a 500 million reserve funded by the 
oil industry to clean up spills said ed manning a mccarthy aide 
who wrote the legislation 
davis said oil companies have indicated they are willing to 
contribute a total of 10 million to such a fund 
the bill also would require each company operating tankers in 
state waters to meet a 400 million insurance requirement to pay 
for potential legal costs in the event of a spill manning said 
had the bill been law british petroleum co plc which 
chartered the american trader could have been required to pay an 
estimated 25 million penalty to the state davis said 
a november ballot initiative that would enact similar prevention 
and cleanup measures and prohibit new drilling in california waters 
also was expected to receive a boost from the spill 
some activists said the spill should remind californians and the 
rest of the nation about the hazards of reliance on oil as an 
energy source 
the whole issue is that every gallon of oil we save is one 
less gallon of oil that must be pumped and transported and one less 
gallon that can spill bob hattoy regional director of the 
sierra club of southern california said in huntington beach 
the longer we remain addicted to oil the more we pollute the 
air we breathe warm the globe despoil our landscape and run the 
risk of oil spills sydney butler vice president for 
conservation at the wilderness society said in a statement 
