the countrys first allcommunist 
government was sworn in thursday after formerly docile allies and 
other opposition leaders ignored appeals to help run the country 
until elections in may 
as parliament president stanko todorov installed the new 
20member cabinet several hundred people protested outside 
demanding the resignation of the lawmaking body because it approved 
the new government 
premier andrei lukanov told the national assembly the 
economically stagnant country is in deep crisis and he pledged 
to move toward a market economy that favors the equality of all 
property including private and foreign ownership 
his comments broadcast over government radio appeared to 
signal determination to institute some of the same reforms already 
in place by other warsaw pact countries further on the road to 
democracy 
longtime hardline communist party chief todor zhivkov was 
ousted in november but parliament did not abolish the partys 
guaranteed grip on power until jan 15 
the cabinet replaces one that resigned last week and included 
some members of the agrarian party which had been a docile ally of 
the communists for decades 
in the immediate postwar years some other parties later 
absorbed by the communists or banned were also represented in 
governments 
