<TEXT>
douglas long chairman of the british weekly 
newspaper the sunday correspondent and cofounder of the daily 
paper the independent has died his family reported thursday he 
was 65 
long died wednesday of cancer of the liver at royal marsden 
hospital after a short illness 
born in london long was educated at wandsworth school in south 
london but before he had time to start a career he was swept up 
into world war ii serving as a cavalryman in the indian army 
after the war he became a reporter and later a feature writer 
on the nowdefunct london newspaper the daily graphic he later 
worked for the daily record in glasgow scotland and then became 
scottish editor of the nowdefunct daily herald 
he subsequently moved to london as chief news editor and feature 
editor of the daily herald 
he later became deputy managing director of the mirror group of 
newspapers whose flagship is the tabloid daily mirror and in 1980 
was made deputy chief executive of the group 
when publishing tycoon robert maxwell bought the mirror group in 
1984 long quit to help start up the independent with andreas 
whittam smith the former financial editor of the daily telegraph 
and matthew symonds another former staffer with the daily 
telegraph among others 
the independent was launched in october 1986 with whittam smith 
as editor and swiftly established itself as a serious and respected 
newspaper 
long then left the independent to help launch the sunday 
correspondent of which he was chairman when it hit the newsstands 
sept 17 last year 
he is survived by his wife barbara his son mark and four 
grandchildren 
</TEXT>
