<TEXT>
the food and drug administration has won white 
house approval of stricter regulations about health claims by food 
marketers permitting only truthful and not misleading 
assertions about a narrow range of diseases an agency official 
said thursday 
such claims used to be completely banned but the agency began 
allowing them under a new policy announced in 1987 some members of 
congress have said fda was allowing manufacturers to play 
reckless games in making illfounded claims 
the policy revision to be published in the federal register 
next week is a midcourse correction said the official who 
discussed the draft on condition that he not be identified 
though advertising might come under the policy the agency is 
most concerned with what is carried on the package label he said 
the office of management and budget which reviews draft 
regulations of all executive branch agencies approved the policy 
on wednesday without requesting substantial changes the official 
said 
the new policy will allow health claims only about these topics 
fiber and colon cancer 
fiber and heart disease 
fats and cancer 
fats and heart disease 
sodium and high blood pressure 
calcium and osteoporosis a softening of the bones sometimes 
found in the elderly 
many scientists believe that in some circumstances fiber might 
reduce colon cancer and heart disease fats might increase cancer 
and heart disease high concentrations of sodium increase blood 
pressure and calcium can help prevent osteoporosis 
the new policy will require that any claims be 
truthful and not misleading in the officials words 
limited to describing the relationship between a particular 
food component and a chronic disease 
consistent with a reasonable diet 
supported by fdaapproved summaries of the evidence the agency 
will make available model summaries for industry to use 
until final adoption of the new policy which could take a year 
the agency will enforce it case by case considering whether 
the scientific evidence supports a claim 
there are enough benefits to make a claim in the first place 
whether the good outweighs the bad in following the 
sellers advice the official said this point might for example 
rule out a lowcholesterol food that is high in saturated fats 
since scientists believe saturated fats in the diet are more 
important in forming cholesterol in the blood than diet cholesterol 
itself 
he declined to give examples of current claims the agency could 
act against under the new policy 
however the agency has said it has serious concerns about 
cereals containing husks of psyllium which contain soluble fiber 
fda also has warned the american heart association against its 
new heartguide program to label brands it approves as heart 
healthy with a prominent mark 
the official said the new policy did not directly bear on the 
heart groups action he said he understood the association had 
said it would review the program plans when the new policy was 
published 
