<TEXT>
heads shoulders knees and toes sculpted by some 
of the worlds greatest artists are on display at the musee 
dorsay illustrating that fragments are often more powerful than 
the whole 
the muscled torso of a man falling over backward the curled 
fingers of a tensed hand and the bloodsoaked head of a 
revolutionary martyr are part of a major retrospective on 
fragmented human forms sculpted over the centuries 
the exhibit titled the body in pieces is here through june 
3 when it travels to frankfurt west germany it is a comprehensive 
look at how artists from michaelangelo to rodin have been 
fascinated with buttocks breasts and biceps heads hands and 
haunches 
some of the works are simply the remnants of things past the 
whole having been lost long ago other works such as rodins study 
of praying hands were conceived as fragments from the start 
fragmenting the human form reinforces our perception of what 
remains wrote ann pingeot in the 343page exhibition catalogue 
the show features hundreds of pieces of sculpture by rodin 
aristide maillol emileantoine bourdelle and photographs drawings 
and even a tree of waxen hands 
a major highlight is lorenzo da mugianos torso of louis xii 
dating from 1508 the hands and head were tacked on from 1798 to 
1790 when scholars believed that broken was not beautiful 
today art critics are delighted that the armless venus de milo 
did not suffer the same fate 
bourdelle a french sculptor wrote in 1937 its so sad to 
think that there are people still searching for the venus de milos 
gesture and who instead of appreciating it as it is if they were 
capable of seeing it want to find out at all cost what action the 
statue represented 
fragments became fashionable in the 20th century as a genre 
reflecting the philosophy that less is more 
michaelangelo was the first to conceive of an incomplete statue 
as a finished work rodin followed in that tradition three 
centuries later and made fragments the cornerstone of his 
composition 
the exhibition features dozens of his works which have long 
been considered as experimental and which are virtually unknown 
to the general public 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

