<TEXT>
this smoky smelly city is 
classified by ecologists as an environmental catastrophe hidden 
until now by the iron curtain the word is out that its pollution 
is killing its people 
with the collapse of the iron curtain across eastern europe 
bitterfeld has become exposed to the outside world deadly chemical 
canals bubble past homes smokestacks spew sickening yellow and 
black toxic emissions above a poisoned wasteland 
the rev peter heyroth a lutheran pastor prays the city about 
75 miles southwest of berlin can be saved 
for years the seriousness of the environmental damage was 
kept secret he said only now are we beginning to find out how 
frightening the situation is 
ecologists call bitterfeld a chemical bomb with a shortened fuse 
one of europes most dangerously polluted cities east germany is 
one of europes most dangerously polluted countries 
its emissions of some toxic substances like forestkilling 
sulphur dioxide exceed those of all other european nations 
scientists say 
about twothirds of east germanys lakes and rivers are believed 
to be badly or moderately contaminated and large parts of its 
forests are dying as well 
west german companies plan to help clean up areas in east 
germany like bitterfeld but the task will cost billions and 
require years to complete 
the bitterfeld area with its huge chemical complexes and 
smokespewing coalfired power plants is a major contributor to 
east germanys ominous ecological woes 
the 60000 people in the greater bitterfeld area live in the 
toxic shadow of two giant stateowned combines the ckb and fkc 
chemicalproducing complexes and several coalburning power plants 
whose emissions include sulphur dioxide 
black coal soot lies in layers on the citys homes and 
businesses 
noxious odors waft from several ponds filled with chemical 
wastes and vast stretches of the areas three rivers are totally 
devoid of life 
on windy days the chemical stench in parts of bitterfeld and 
neighboring wolfen is so bad that people shutter their windows in 
often futile attempts to keep the fumes out 
open coal pits the size of large villages have created a 
wasteland outside the residential areas adding to the toxic 
grimness 
hans zimmermann a local ecologist said liquid chemical wastes 
without the rigid cleansing treatments usual in the west have 
badly contaminated the soil and groundwater 
west german scientists have expressed shock that bitterfeld area 
residents drink the milk of cows that graze on pastureland that 
could be contaminated by toxic substances 
zimmermann said the most frightening thing for him is that no 
one knows for sure what the longterm health dangers might be but 
suspects the wastewater includes highly hazardous dioxins 
oncesecret documents show the chemical wastewaters are also 
laced with sulphates huge amounts of chlorine mercury and other 
highly toxic substances according to the jan 8 issue of the west 
german newsmagazine der spiegel 
bitterfeld has been the site of at least one major chemical 
accident 
in 1968 a huge explosion at ckb killed about 70 people 
zimmermann said 
he added that over the past few years a number of smaller 
accidents have occurred at ckb a major producer of a wide range of 
chemical products including herbicides pesticides and paints but 
information about the accidents was always kept inhouse said 
zimmermann 
area residents suffer from a variety of ailments including lung 
diseases cancer and slow bone development among children experts 
and residents say 
recent western tests found that bitterfelds residents have an 
average life span at least five years shorter than that of other 
east german citizens 
of those people who die early here i bury more who have 
perished from cancer than anything else pastor heyroth said 
in wolfen luisi schmidt points to a giant pond filled with 
liquid chemical wastes next to her home 
signs reading danger lifeendangering do not enter 
surround the pond 
it stinks like the devil here sometimes said ms schmidt 
who looks much older than her 51 years and has sores at her 
hairline and on her face 
a young woman died of cancer not so long ago she added 
she was only 35 it was that stinking cesspool 
zimmermann and heyroth say one of the main problems in 
bitterfeld is that east germanys former stalinist leaders never 
bothered to modernize the chemicalproduction factories and power 
plants 
they also decided it was more important to pursue chemical 
production at a breakneck pace regardless of the possible health 
hazards 
east germanys ecological problems are widespread and there seem 
to be at least two reasons people have tolerated it for so long 
the communists refusal to say exactly what the dangers were and 
the lure of salaries up to three times as high for chemical plant 
workers than for other citizens 
this city has been totally subjugated by these gigantic 
chemical complexes ecologist zimmermann said and in the 
process it has died 
