<TEXT>
in the brave new world of the telephone company 
its no longer enough to listen to computers now you have to talk 
to them 
at the tone please say your name electronic operators are 
telling collect callers around the country the machines then ask 
customers at the other end if theyll pay the charges please say 
yes or no 
the system years in the works and just now arriving marks a 
new tier in telephone technology a computer that not only delivers 
messages or directs callers to hit buttons but responds to the 
human voice 
it understands when you say yes or no said preston peek 
spokesman for northern telecom inc a leading developer of 
computer systems that can discern spoken words it asks what you 
want to do and you just tell it 
and its probably coming to a phone company near you 
three of the seven regional phone companies ameritech 
bellsouth and nynex have voice recognition systems for 
collect and thirdparty calls in some areas now two more pacific 
telesis and bell atlantic will soon 
the phone companies eyeing lower costs and a bigger market 
love the technology they say even smarter computer systems ones 
that can make out numbers even city names are near 
its inevitable that everyones going to go to computerized 
voices said atampt spokesman bryant steele its costsaving 
its more efficient 
but that delight is not universally shared 
after some initial grousing people will eventually go ahead 
and live with it said dr kenyon degreene an expert in 
humanmachine relationships however a price eventually has to 
be paid 
that price said degreene a psychologist and professor of 
systems management at the university of southern california is the 
burgeoning impersonality of society 
when a computer demands specific words from a telephone caller 
control seems to rest with the machine degreene said and because 
many people dont understand the workings of technology theres 
an implied threat there 
the person senses that he cannot use freeflowing speech hes 
being constrained the computer is controlling him it can be 
simply frustrating he said people adapt to it but only by 
filing it away subconsciously as another annoyance of living in our 
technological world 
there are other problems because of interference background 
noise or other glitches the computers do not always recognize 
words they eventually switch to a human operator but only after 
several tries for now they recognize only english and callers 
once familiar with the system still have to listen to the 
computers spiel before answering 
there is an out however callers can ignore the computers 
instructions and just hit o to get a human operator 
if speaking to a computer is annoying its also fascinating 
for its first trick asking the collect callers name the system 
simply records the answer and plays it back to the call recipient 
after announcing the call is collect 
the next part is harder after asking if the recipient will 
accept the call the system compares the yes or no response 
to a soundwave matrix based on recordings of tens of thousands of 
people uttering those words 
it makes its best guess as to whether you said yes or 
no said candice kamm a specialist in speech recognition at 
bell comunications research inc in livingston nj 
the computer guesses right about 98 percent of the time she 
said provided the person does what theyre supposed to do 
she predicts customers will adjust noting that phone users grew 
accustomed to answering machines and later to the computerized 
voices providing numbers to directory assistance callers 
michigan bell gave the northern telecom system its first tryout 
starting in june in grand rapids now its expanding computerized 
operators to detroit pontiac and then across the state the system 
is newly arrived in florida ohio and new york 
nationally us telephone callers placed 579 million collect 
and thirdparty calls in 1988 
multiply that by the amount of seconds each operator spends 
handling one of those calls and youll get an idea of the 
savings said peek the northern telecom spokesman 
further savings are ahead half the nations telephones are 
rotary rather than touchtone models and those callers cannot 
punch in credit card numbers but when the computers can recognize 
spoken numbers operators wont be needed to handle those 
creditcard calls 
rotary phones also will become compatible with systems that now 
require touchtone responses to reach an extension for example 
or to hear a recorded train schedule 
and when the systems can understand city names directory 
assistance callers will find themselves queried for that 
information by the computer before an operator completes the 
service again cutting operator time 
us sprint the nations no 3 longdistance phone company says 
by june it will start a voiceactivated dialing system in which 
callers can say their names and a password instead of punching in 
their account codes callers also will be able to dial 
preregistered numbers with spoken orders such as call home 
sprints longdistance competitors atampt and mci communications 
corp are studying voiceactivated services atampt has said some 
services could begin this year mci has no such plans now 
two of the regional phone companies us west and southwestern 
bell have no immediate plans to implement voiceactivated 
services but theyre looking into it we consider its better 
customer service to have live operators said us west spokesman 
stephen holder and we dont believe the technology performs well 
enough yet 
spokesmen for michigan bell and new york telephone co reported 
few customer complaints and said they were not laying off 
operators but they said the savings should enable them to handle 
increasing demand without hiring more workers new england 
telephone which is starting the service this month said it might 
reduce some operators hours 
linda meltzer a phone company analyst for drexel burnham 
lambert predicted layoffs down the line saying theyll need 
less employees as they become automated 
companies will push technology whenever they can as long as 
theres an economic advantage to it said degreene the usc 
professor 
while staff reductions save money for a company it 
precipitates all kinds of social problems he said it puts the 
companys problem out into society in general what will we do with 
these people who are no longer employed by the telephone company 
</TEXT>
