<TEXT>
if there is a collapse of housing prices it is a 
mysterious one because it hasnt shown up in the statistics 
the most reliable national numbers obtainable show existinghome 
prices are higher than they were last year affordability 
measurements are fair to good mortgage costs though higher 
recently are below yearago levels 
its a picture not of deterioration but of stability but 
somehow it isnt painted that way 
discovering the reason why isnt easy any more than it is easy 
to explain how the media can carry so many stories about layoffs 
and plant shutdowns while the jobless rate remains stuck at 53 
percent since last summer 
one possible clue relates to the importance people place on jobs 
and homes few things are more important so it is possible that 
any suggestion of bad news becomes exaggerated out of proportion 
perhaps 
norman flynn of madison wis president of the national 
association of realtors offers another idea 
speaking of condominium sales he commented recently that 
because of its large share of condos and coops when the 
northeast condo market has slight tremors the rest of the country 
experiences an earthquake 
that inference fits into a larger one involving not just housing 
but politics and economics it is the eastern establishment effect 
or the egocentric tendency for ideas and events in that area to be 
maximized 
but oddly even in the northeast where in some localities 
apartment coops and condos have sat empty for a year prices 
overall have held in 1988 the median price was 110600 
according to the nar last year it was 110800 
other statistics offer little more evidence of a collapse 
sales of existing singlefamily homes last year totaled 359 
million units which indeed was down by 46 percent from the 
previous year but that previous year was the strongest of the 
entire decade of the 1980s 
in prices there is even less evidence of problems the national 
median price for existing singlefamily homes in december was 
92500 or 43 percent above the yearearlier median of 88700 
even in the northeast where economies have slowed from boom 
times the median price for 1989 rose to 145200 from 143000 
the only clue to resolving the mystery might lie in sales 
figures for the northeast they fell in 1989 existing 
singlefamily sales were 585000 down 88000 units from the year 
before and the lowest since 1984 
moreover last years sales decline was the third in a row since 
the decades peak sales of 703000 units in 1986 much of the 
decline was in the larger more prominent cities where change 
could become magnified 
in certain local areas throughout the northeast both building 
and selling activity all but came to a halt in some communities 
near new york city for example the average selling time was close 
to 250 days three years ago it was not uncommon for houses to 
generate bids in the first week of listing 
theres a random assortment of other clues to account for the 
impression of a housing debacle among them 
homebuilding did decline for all 1989 total residential 
permits fell 79 percent to 1340600 lowest since 1982 according 
to us housing markets a national survey published by lomas 
mortgage usa 
the decline was steepest in the northeast 186 percent and the 
south 113 percent 
commercial building also declined in addition many owners of 
existing buildings and their bankers ran into highly publicized 
financial problems but very few of these disasters involved 
singlefamily housing 
the days of putting tags on houses far beyond the existing 
market level in hopes that buyers would chase prices ended 
abruptly as a result asking prices did fall but not necessarily 
below prices of a year earlier 
generally speaking numbers often confirm impressions this time 
they are at odds it just doesnt add up as they say 
