<TEXT>
colombian officials battle a cocaine 
establishment so ruthless and powerful that their best hope is to 
ship its leaders when they can be caught to the united states 
the peruvian government encounters not entrenched highly 
successful businessmen but peasants whose livelihood is the coca 
crop and leftist guerrillas who battle the government in the name 
of the poor 
in bolivia impoverished farmers eagerly accept government 
payments in return for destroying coca crops on which they spend 
more money than they make but the government wonders what the 
peasants will do with themselves if theyre not growing the raw 
material for cocaine 
the leaders of these nations will meet with president bush on 
thursday to coordinate their efforts in what they say will be an 
unstoppable assault on drug traffickers but each faces his own 
reality and must approach the war on drugs in his own way 
here is the situation in the three andean countries which 
together account for most of the worlds cocaine production 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
over the years colombian traffickers led by the medellin and 
cali cartels have murdered thousands of their countrymen and 
turned entire regions into cocaineproduction centers 
so strong are the cartels ringleaders that president virgilio 
barco fearful that his nations judicial system is not up to the 
task has made hunting down and extraditing the nations top 
traffickers his first priority in the war on drugs 
plainly he feels justice has a better chance of prevailing in 
the united states where 80 percent of the cocaine supply comes 
from the two cartels than in colombia 
colombian police have been going hog wild on locating 
colombians for extradition said a knowledgeable us official 
adding but they havent been able to go after the cocaine labs 
at the same time 
the governments focus has indeed shifted in the six months of 
the extradition campaign from targeting the jungle labs that 
process raw coca leaves from peru and bolivia to focusing on the 
men who call the shots 
theres a downside to barcos efforts 
the us official who spoke on the condition of anonymity said 
that the supply of cocaine leaving colombia after taking a sharp 
dive in the weeks after the campaign began has rebounded nearly to 
its earlier level 
the official said independent traffickers not associated with 
any organization have filled in the gaps torn in the cartels by the 
government offensive 
despite its failure to make a lasting dent in cocaine output 
the colombian crackdown has shown some results 
the government reported recently that authorities have taken 
over 777 of the traffickers properties worth millions of dollars 
fourteen drug suspects have been sent to the united states and 
one leader of the medellin cartel gonzalo rodriguez gacha was 
killed in a dec 15 gunfight 
authorities last year seized nearly 27 million gallons of 
imported industrial chemicals used to process coca into cocaine 
the year before less than 1 million gallons of such chemicals were 
confiscated 
the jump was astounding and proved to the world that colombia 
was serious about fighting cocaine trafficking said the us 
official 
the acting chief of the national police gen carlos arturo 
casadiego put it this way in a recent interview 
this war will continue until there are no more drug 
traffickers walking freely in colombia that is our goal it is not 
negotiable 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
since september 30 or so us drug agents contract pilots and 
mechanics have been launching raids with peruvian police against 
jungle drug laboratories and clandestine airstrips 
but rebel activity in the upper huallaga valley where most of 
the countrys coca crop is grown has kept the agents from 
operating freely last year they pulled out of the valley for seven 
months after an american helicopter pilot was wounded by gunfire 
maoist shining path guerrillas controlling much of the valley 
offer protection to drug traffickers in exchange for a share of the 
profits the rebels also make sure the traffickers do not cheat the 
peasant coca growers 
peru accounts for 60 percent of the worlds coca leaf crop 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in bolivia where drugrelated violence is much less of a 
problem than in colombia or peru the government has made some 
gains against coca growing in recent months with a croperadication 
program that pays farmers to destroy their coca fields 
in december and january farmers voluntarily destroyed a record 
512 acres of coca in chapare the region where 80 percent of the 
countrys coca plants are found 
farmers get the equivalent of 800 for every acre they destroy 
peasants are lining up for the money because 100 pounds of coca 
leaf now sells for 5 to 7 but costs about 30 to grow 
in the last few months the jaime paz zamora government has 
made significant progress in law enforcement eradication 
interdiction and crop substitution programs us ambassador 
robert s gelbard said in a recent interview 
but he added that colombias war against traffickers was 
partially responsible for the bolivian success the colombian 
crackdown lowered the price paid for coca because demand for the 
leaf fell when traffickers dropped out of sight 
bolivia accounts for onethird of international coca leaf 
production 
bolivian authorities worry as do those in peru what peasants 
will do with themselves if the eradication program is a 
thoroughgoing success 
an estimated 300000 peasants in chapare depend on coca 
production for their livlihood many have complained that the 
government is eradicating the crop without offering an alternative 
and that they benefited little from 40 million provided by the 
united states for crop substitution last year 
the government in peru says as many as 200000 peruvians make 
their living by growing the coca bush president alan garcia has 
resisted eradication programs such as the one in bolivia because he 
does not want to drive displaced coca farmers into the hands of the 
maoist guerrillas 
the approach to the drug fight may vary but one thing all three 
nations agree on is the need to gain more economic assistance from 
the united states in return for their participation 
the bush administration has earmarked 270 million this year for 
colombia bolivia and peru but some foreign officials say all 
three countries will likely ask for more 
