the future of the government program that 
insures millions of americans pensions is at stake in a supreme 
court case that will be argued this month with federal officials 
warning that an adverse ruling could eventually force a huge 
taxpayer bailout 
at issue is whether ltv steel co will succeed in dumping 
billions of dollars in pension costs onto the governments pension 
benefit guaranty corporation setting a precedent that could lead 
to similar maneuvers by other companies 
labor secretary elizabeth dole says the case will have 
farreaching ramifications for the retirement security of workers 
and pensioners across the country 
the court must decide whether the pbgc acted properly in 
ordering ltv steel a subsidiary of the dallasbased ltv corp to 
reassume responsibility for three pension plans a federal appeals 
court already has ruled against the pbgc the supreme court is 
scheduled to hear the arguments feb 27 
ltv faced with a declining steel market declared bankrupcy in 
1986 and notified the pbgc it could not pay into its pension plans 
which were underfinanced by 23 billion the burden then fell to 
the national pension insurance agency which collects premiums from 
the companies that hold pension plans for 30 million american 
workers 
