<TEXT>
the barriers to eliminating guinea worm disease 
a disabling infection that strikes 10 million people a year mostly 
in africa are political and financial not technical us health 
officials say 
in addition theres a failure to recognize the opportunity 
that exists to get rid of the disease the centers for disease 
control says 
guinea worm disease dracunculiasis occurs in 16 african 
countries india and pakistan and is transmitted through drinking 
water contaminated with larvae of the guinea worm nigeria alone 
reported more than 650000 cases in 1988 the last year for which 
statistics are available when ingested larvae can mature in the 
stomach or intestinal tract becoming worms up to 47 inches long 
after incubation of about a year they emerge through the skin 
usually in the legs 
the result is intense pain and incapacitattion for up to three 
months although recovery is usually complete some patients can be 
left permanently disabled if joints are affected by the worm or 
associated infections 
the disease can be prevented by filtering boiling or chemically 
treating water the major thrust of eradication is to teach people 
how to treat their water not trying to overhaul the third worlds 
sanitation systems overnight said dr robert kaiser head of the 
cdc division of parasitic diseases 
the approach in the long term is providing safe and adequate 
supplies to everyone but this is a costly longterm kind of 
goal he said there are more immediate and easier approaches 
to the problem that are less costly 
</TEXT>
