<TEXT>
the administration hopes to complete by early 
may a ussoviet trade pact that presidents bush and mikhail 
gorbachev can sign at their scheduled summit meeting a month later 
the first round of talks on what would be the first attempt for 
an economic accord with the soviets since the early 1970s will open 
here monday us trade representative carla hills said 
through these negotiations we hope to encourage economic 
reform within the soviet union as it moves toward a more 
marketdriven economy mrs hills told the senate finance 
committee wednesday 
the panels chairman sen lloyd bentsen dtexas warned mrs 
hills any accord reached with the soviets could run into trouble on 
capitol hill if lawmakers arent consulted along the way 
bentsen expressed anger he was not advised beforehand by 
administration officials that bush would promise gorbachev a new 
round of trade talks at their malta summit meeting in december 
president nixon signed a trade agreement with the soviets in 
1972 but it was never ratified by the senate 
if the nixon administration had consulted with congress i 
dont think the bush administration would have the kind of 
limitations it has on it now bentsen said im deeply 
concerned that we dont see a repetition of that 
the talks follow mutual pledges by bush and gorbachev to 
accelerate a normalization of ussoviet trade and economic 
relations in response to the wave of democratic reforms sweeping 
the soviet bloc 
as part of the accord which has to be approved by congress the 
united states would waive the 1974 jacksonvanik provisions that 
now require the soviets to pay several times the normal tariffs 
charged most other countries on their exports to us markets 
a successful agreement will also create opportunities for us 
businesses to expand trade and commercial activity with the soviet 
union mrs hills said 
the us negotiating team will be led by deputy us trade 
representative julies katz the head of the soviet team is yuriy 
chumakov deputy minister of foreign economic relations 
administration officials envision the accord removing a 300 
million ceiling on loans and loan guarantees from the us 
exportimport bank to finance soviet purchases of american exports 
other expected provisions include relaxing restrictions on 
hightech exports and reversing us opposition to loans and loan 
guarantees from the international monetary fund and world bank 
in addition us capital investments in the soviet union could 
become eligible for the first time for insurance protection from 
the overseas private investment corp similar opic restrictions on 
hungary and poland were lifted as part of an aid bill last fall 
mrs hills said the administration will seek protections for 
us businesses in the accord including safeguards from import 
surges protection of intellectual property rights such as patents 
and copyrights and greater freedom to do business in the soviet 
union 
