<TEXT>
police officials said today they plan to send 
investigators to europe next week to try to trace the source of 
bogus japanese gold coins with a face value of 71 million japans 
biggest counterfeiting case ever 
a police spokesman however declined to reveak the 
investigators destination 
japans kyodo news service said the investigators would go to 
switzerland from which japanese coin dealers had imported 103000 
gold coins all believed to be fakes since march 1988 
the counterfeit coins were first discovered late last month when 
a company tried to deposit a batch with a bank police said more 
fake coins have been found since then including a cache found in 
the vault of the bank of japan the countrys central bank the new 
york times reported today 
the counterfeits are of a 100000yen or 687 coin issued by 
japan in 1986 and 1987 to commemorate the 60th year of emperor 
hirohitos reign hirohito died in january 1989 
the fake coins like the real commemorative ones are made of 
gold but because the commemorative issue sells for almost 2 times 
the value of the gold content in the coins counterfeiting could 
prove lucrative 
the huge number of the commemorative coins issued is another 
factor said koichiro ishihara managing director of the monthly 
coin magazine published in tokyo it would make a challenging 
job for the authorities to find the fakes among millions of coins 
in circulation 
the bank of japan issued 10 million of the commemorative coins 
in 1986 and an additional 1 million coins the following year 
a bank of japan official said the fakes like the genuine coins 
each contain 20 grams or twothirds of an ounce of pure gold 
worth about 40000 yen or 278 based on open market prices for 
gold gold closed at 41810 an ounce on the new york commodity 
exchange wednesday 
still the price of the commemorative coins remains set at 
100000 yen 
the first counterfeits were found on jan 29 when taisei stamp 
and coin co of tokyo presented 1000 coins for deposit at a branch 
of fuji bank in downtown tokyo 
taisei executives told police that the company had imported the 
coins through paul davis 38 a british coin dealder based in 
london for 98000 yen each 
police investigators then found that rimpac gold co and daruma 
international galleries both of tokyo had imported a total of 
102000 such coins through davis and another european coin dealer 
between march 1988 and january this year 
we suspect all these coins to be bogus the police spokesman 
said adding that the authorities have yet to verify that 
police have said some 8000 of the 103000 coins were checked 
last week and all were found to be bogus the forged coins had 
slight flaws on both surfaces visible only by microscope they 
said 
a fuji bank official said last week he felt the fake coins were 
lighter in color than genuine ones otherwise he said they looked 
and weighed the same as real coins 
it was not known immediately how many of the imported coins have 
been sold to private investors in japan 
davis came to tokyo last friday to answer police questions 
police officials said wednesday davis maintains that he only acted 
as a middleman and he still believes the coins are genuine 
