<TEXT>
new york city has filed a multimilliondollar 
lawsuit against exxon corp over a 567000gallon oil spill from a 
pipeline into the arthur kill waterway mayor david dinkins said 
the exxon oil spill is a disaster that could have been 
prevented should have never happened and has permanently scarred 
the environmental landscape dinkins said wednesday 
the lawsuit filed in state court seeks a 10 million fine 
reimbursement to the city for cleanup costs and full restoration 
of the kill a waterway between staten island and new jersey and 
adjacent wetlands 
the lawsuit also alleges fraud on the part of exxon at least 
once every three months from jan 1 1984 through the third 
quarter of last year for submitting reports to the fire department 
that an oil pipeline and leak detection system were working 
properly said corporation counsel victor kovner 
exxon has admitted publicly that for approximately the last 12 
years the leak detection system has frequently signaled a leak 
when none existed the lawsuit said 
it said exxons repeated prior claims that it had been 
successfully tested suggests that exxon had a policy and practice 
of disregarding the truth 
exxon spokesman douglas walt said the company was disappointed 
because it has been participating with 10 city state and federal 
agencies in negotiations aimed at addressing the concerns outlined 
in the citys lawsuit 
we continue to hope that these discussions will result in the 
development of a mutually agreeable plan that will eliminate the 
need for the lawsuit and in no way are we backing away from this 
effort walt said in a statement we have provided a definitive 
study plan and have been waiting for a response 
dinkins had indicated early last month that he hoped the city 
would not have to sue exxon which he called new yorks corporate 
neighbor and that the company would commit itself to reimbursing 
the city for its costs 
kovner said wednesday that exxon had assured the state it would 
pay for costs for which it was liable but that it did not make a 
clear commitment to pay for damages to the city 
the lawsuit said the spill continues to contaminate the waters 
of the arthur kill adjacent kill van kull and other streams 
creeks and rivers and caused the death of an increasing number of 
waterfowl 
