the new york times co reported thursday it lost 
19 million in the fourth quarter citing regional economic 
weakness and previouslydisclosed charges involving its forest 
products investment and costs of staffing reductions 
for the year the media concern said its profit climbed 59 
percent principally because of a big gain on the sale of its cable 
television system 
the company said its loss in the fourth quarter amounted to 24 
cents a share in contrast to earnings of 504 million or 64 cents 
per share in 1988 
fourthquarter revenue rose 44 percent to 4702 million from 
4500 million a year earlier 
the company said the weak new york regional economy reduced 
advertising lineage by 56 percent for the quarter at the new york 
times its flagship newspaper 
the latest results also reflected a charge of 57 cents a share 
for the establishment of a valuation reserve against the companys 
investment in its forest products group and costs of voluntary 
staff reductions at the times 
the fourthquarter results also were reduced by 11 cents a share 
in the quarter due to structuring costs associated with its recent 
acquisitions of mccalls golf world us and sailing world 
magazines and by 3 cents a share as a result of a legal settlement 
with independent home delivery dealers 
the company said that excluding the special factors earnings 
per share would have been 47 cents in the fourth quarter 
