<TEXT>
britains highest court of appeal ruled against 
bordens inc thursday in a battle over the right to sell lemon 
juice in squeezable containers 
the law lords britains highest judiciary body upheld a 
previous high court ruling that bars borden from selling its 
plastic lemons filled with reconstituted lemon juice in britain 
because shoppers could confuse bordens realemon with a similar 
british product jif 
borden issued a statement from its headquarters in new york 
saying the firm disagreed with the decision but would abide by it 
jifs manufacturer reckitt and colman won an injunction three 
years ago barring borden from marketing realemon in any container 
so nearly resembling the jif lemonshaped container 
borden had argued that it would be impossible to compete without 
causing initial confusion because jif was the only product of its 
kind in the british market 
the judge disagreed and said that if the borden product were 
packaged differently put in a box or shaped like a lemon segment 
the problem would be solved 
its unfortunate that uk consumers will not be able to make 
their choice in the marketplace based on price and quality of 
competitive and conspicuously labeled products bordens 
statement said 
the threeyear legal battle is believed to have cost the two 
companies 25 million in legal fees 
lord bridge one of the five judges who heard the case said 
reckitt and colman had been given a de facto monopoly in 
naturalsized plastic lemons 
a trader selling plastic lemons would never be permitted to 
register a lemon as his trade mark but reckitt and colman have 
achieved the result indirectly that a container designed to look 
like a real lemon is to be treated per se as distinctive of their 
goods he said 
bridge said he would have liked to avoid this result but he 
could not fault the legal reasoning and agreed with the other 
judges in dismissing bordens appeal 
another law lord lord jauncey said he did not believe that 
jifs makers were being given a monopoly the ruling he said 
merely meant that borden had not taken adequate steps to 
differentiate its package from that of reckitt and colman so 
consumers would not be deceived 
borden said it would continue to sell its lemon product in 
bottles in britain and throughout europe and its lemonshaped 
containers in france and norway 
</TEXT>
