<DOCNO> AP900208-0284 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the federal communications commission on 
thursday reversed a yearold policy allowing white knight 
applicants to gain broadcast licenses saying such 11thhour 
resolutions encourage sham applications 
an attorney representing a group that challenged the 
commissions dec 23 1988 decision to approve a settlement 
agreement for a new fm station in marco fla said thursdays 
action suggests a more aggressive regulatory posture under new fcc 
chairman alfred sikes 
this is an absolute uturn on a policy adopted by the 
reaganera fcc a year ago said andrew schwartzman executive 
director of the media access project 
schwartzmans group appealed the fccs approval of a pact in 
which rowland gulf radio inc which was not an original applicant 
for the new station license paid off one of the applicants 
affirmative broadcasting to substitute rowlands name on the 
application 
in return rowland paid off the other six competing applicants 
the fcc said 
the rationale behind the white knight approach which the 
commission first adopted in the marco case during the chairmanship 
of dennis r patrick was to avoid lengthy and costly comparative 
application hearings in which a number of competing parties try to 
prove theyre the most worthy applicant 
the fcc said the white knight approach could get stations on the 
air more quickly thus better serving the public interest 
but the fcc said it was granting reconsideration of its own 
motion disapproving the marco agreement and reopening the license 
proceeding because it was concerned that approval would encourage 
the filing of sham applications conceived only for the purpose of 
entering into profitable settlement agreements 
the commission said it found that although approval of the marco 
settlement would expedite service to the public this was 
outweighed by the fact that approving the marco agreement would 
create an economic incentive for individuals with no real interest 
in building and operating broadcast stations to file sham 
applications in future cases 
schwartzman said thursdays decision was a very important 
policy reversal that will impact a very substantial number of 
pending cases around the country it signals again that the 
sikes commission is going to take a much more aggressive stance on 
regulatory issues 
schwartzman who had appealed to the fcc on behalf of the united 
church of christs office of communications and two florida 
residents said the white knight method amounted to a private 
auction 
it enables the least qualified possible applicant to get the 
station as long as theyre rich enough to buy off the better 
qualified applicants schwartzman said 
the fcc in the early 1980s legalized unlimited payoffs between 
competing applicants which critics said led to a flood of 
frivolous and sham applications by parties not really interested in 
operating stations 
in march 1989 in a move designed to reduce the number of 
nuisance applications from profiteers the fcc banned all 
settlement payments prior to an initial licensing decision by the 
commission and limited payments after a license hearing to 
legitimate expenses incurred by the withdrawing applicant 
the applicants for the florida license were rebecca radio of 
marco emerald sea broadcasting inc affirmative broadcasting 
corp showcase communications inc marco minority associates 
susan g and william r gaston and marco skywave inc 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

