<DOCNO> AP900208-0290 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal securities regulators are exploring 
what to do about a kind of investment scheme known as a blank 
check blind pool that often victimizes small investors a senate 
panel was told thursday 
blank check blind pools are public stock offerings in which the 
issuer doesnt spell out how it plans to use the money raised 
critics of such pools charge they are often sham corporations 
brought to the marketplace as vehicles for shady purposes 
they were discussed by several witnesses testifying before the 
securities subcommittee of the senate banking housing and urban 
affairs committee which is looking at ways to protect small 
investors from penny stock fraud and other scams 
we need more tools to combat the problem susan e bryant 
administrator of the oklahoma securities department told the panel 
which was chaired by sen richard h bryan dnev 
last week bryan introduced a bill to protect small investors 
the bill which would allow the securities and exchange 
commission to bar such blank check blind pools from registering 
their securities contained provisions sought by the sec to beef up 
their enforcement powers 
last week sec chairman richard c breeden said he wanted the 
ability to to issue cease and desist orders against suspected 
wrongdoers without having to go to courtm first 
breeden also said congress should affirm federal judges rights 
to bar repeat securities law offenders from serving as officers or 
director of public companies 
on the blank check blind pool richard ketchum head of the 
secs division of market regulation conceded it is a vehicle 
that has been used for fraudulent activity particularly the penny 
stock market more and more frquently 
but he and joseph i goldstein head of the secs penny stock 
task force cautioned that clearer definitions were needed 
goldstein said he has asked the sec division of economic 
analysis to study the issue to see if further regulatory steps 
should be taken 
fraud involving penny stocks lowcost highrisk securities 
trading for as little as a penny a share is estimated to cost 
american investors 2 billion a year 
its very very hard to recover it said goldstein adding 
that the most effective defense against penny stock fraud is an 
educated investor 
penny stocks which are usually not listed on any stock exchange 
or national stock quotation system are not illegal and often not 
fraudulent but the scarcity of information about them and the 
limited amount of surveillance they come under make them prone to 
numerous fraud schemes 
one victim who managed to recover most of the 17000 she and 
her husband lost to a penny stock fraud artist said the experience 
was devastating 
losing the money was terrible being lied to and misled by 
people we thought we could trust was worse said debra thomason 
a secretary from elberton ga 
her husband bobby an electrician said the senators might 
wonder how the couple got in such a fix 
the only thing i can tell you is that we trusted these people 
just the same way you trust your doctor or you would trust your 
mechanic if you took your car in and he said you needed brakes 
youre not going to sit there and argue with him thomason said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

