<DOCNO> AP900208-0293 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
researchers said thursday they have 
discovered a new electrical power source that could replace 
traditional rechargeable batteries to supply emergency backup power 
the system is a small fuel cell that converts gas to electricity 
using thin films 
bellcore scientist christopher dyer who discovered the process 
compared it to a solar cell but said it is powered by gases 
instead of sunlight 
he described it as a very clean power source that is fueled 
by hydrogen and oxygen leaving water as the only byproduct 
however the applications are limited until the device can be 
increased in size bellcore the research arm for several regional 
telephone companies is looking for manufacturing partners 
the thumbsize laboratory prototype generates electricity when 
hydrogen or other fuel gases are blown over two electrodes 
separated by a thin membrane in the presence of oxygen 
it could replace batteries if we could make it somewhat bigger 
than what we have dyer said adding that a fuel cell does not 
need to be recharged like a battery fuel cells run as long as 
there is a constant supply of gas 
dyer said bellcore acquired a patent for the device last fall 
a description of the experiment appears in the feb 8 1990 
issue of nature a prestigious london science journal 
the announcement was made by bellcore a research group for the 
seven baby bell regional phone companies ameritech bell 
atlantic bellsouth nynex pacific bell southwestern bell corp 
and us west as well as cincinnati bell and the southern new 
england telephone co 
