<TEXT>
senate leaders said thursday they were close 
to agreement with the bush administration on compromise clean air 
legislation but environmentalists charged the closeddoor talks 
were weakening the bill too much 
key senators and administration officals have been meeting for 
more than a week in an attempt to craft an air pollution control 
package that will avert a divisive floor fight 
majority leader george mitchell dmaine said that while the 
talks were making progress in key areas differences remained 
over how much to toughen automobile emissions standards to reduce 
urban smog 
mitchell who had hoped a compromise package could be agreed 
upon this week said he now has ruled out an agreement before the 
upcoming weeklong congressional recess 
environmentalists charged that the bill approved by the 
environment and public works committee last november was being 
watered down under intense pressure from the white house 
theyre not talking about any strengthening amendments only 
weakening ones said richard ayres executive director of the 
clean air coalition an umbrella group of environmental and public 
health organizations 
the public health is being negotiated away charged dan 
weiss who has been following the clean air debate for the sierra 
club 
mitchell said he expected the criticism but said criticis 
should evaluate the final product against current law the 
maine democrat said substantial progress was being made and that he 
was optimistic a compromise bill that will greatly tighten federal 
air pollution controls could be worked out 
we are making progress agreed sen bob dole rkan the 
senate minority leader but dole said there continued to be deep 
concerns from some senators over the cost of new pollution 
controls especially requirements cutting acid rain which would 
hit a string of midwest states the hardest 
this is not a partisan measure said dole adding that 
opposition and support of the legislation depends on where you 
live 
the senate leaders said that tentative agreements had been 
reached with the administration over controls of industrial toxic 
chemical releases and on contols of smog pollutants on businesses 
and industries in heavily polluted urban centers 
but mitchell said differences continued over provisions that 
would impose tough pollution controls on automobiles after the year 
2003 the administration has called the requirements too expensive 
and argues that a requiring phasing in alternative fuel cars in 
heavily polluted urban areas would be cheaper and as effective 
mitchell said the discussions would resume after the congress 
returns from its presidents day recess feb 20 and that he hoped 
that floor votes on a compromise bill could begin a few days later 
were very close to an agreement much more than 
threefourths agreement said sen max baucus dmont the 
bills democratic floor manager 
but even if a compromise is reached neither mitchell nor dole 
said they could rule out attempts by some senators to stall the 
legislation with a filibuster 
a group of senators largely from the midwest have threatened a 
filibuster if some cost sharing arrangement cannot be worked 
out to ease the expense of complying with expensive acid rain 
provisions especially in the midwest where most of the dirtiest 
plants are located 
both mitchell and the bush administration have ruled out a 
national energy tax or fee to share such costs although some other 
form of cost sharing such as increased emission credits for the 
dirtiest electric power plants continued to be discussed 
cost sharing in the customary sense of a fee or tax is 
dead said baucus 
</TEXT>
