<TEXT>
chinas industrial output fell a sharp 61 
percent in january from a year earlier following a 10 percent drop 
in december according to an official report 
the state statistical bureau in a report carried by the 
official china daily friday attributed the big drop mainly to the 
chinese lunar new year holiday which was marked in february in 
1989 but fell on jan 27 this year 
the lunar new year is chinas biggest holiday and most 
enterprises shut down for three or four days 
but the decline also continued the trend of stagnating economic 
growth that has persisted since mid1989 when a tough government 
austerity program instituted shortly after the june political 
crackdown began to take effect on the economy 
industrial output rose 68 percent in 1989 over the previous 
year but fourthquarter growth was only 07 percent and output in 
october fell 21 percent from the level of october 1988 the first 
monthly decline in a decade 
economists have estimated that up to a third of chinese 
factories have had to suspend or reduce production because tight 
credit policies have left them without operating funds and a 
downturn in demand has led to overstocking and poor sales 
the bureau said industrial output totalled 1278 billion yuan 
272 billion in january with light industry dropping 85 
percent to 62 billion yuan 132 billion and heavy industry 
falling 35 percent to 658 billion yuan 14 billion 
staterun enterprises produced 884 billion yuan 188 
billion down 65 percent and collectively owned firms 341 
billion yuan 726 billion down 71 percent small private firms 
produced most of the rest 
the bureau also said production of most consumer goods fell as a 
result of the continued slump in the retail sales market 
refrigerator production was down 585 percent from a year 
earlier washing machines were down 476 percent color televisions 
393 percent bicycles 373 percent and automobiles 447 percent 
</TEXT>
